ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Ward|first=M.|title=The Livery Collar in Late Medieval England and Wales: Politics, Identity and Affinity|year=2016|publisher=Boydell & Brewer|location=Woodbridge|isbn=978-1-78327-115-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Watts|first=J.|title=Henry VI and the Politics of Kingship|date=1996|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge |isbn=978-0-52165-393-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Wedgwood|first1=J. C.|last2=Holt|first2=A.|lastauthoramp=y|title=History of Parliament: 1439\u20131509|volume=II: Biographies|year=1936|publisher=H. M. Stationery Office|location=London|oclc=847222345|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Wilkinson|first=B.|title=The Later Middle Ages in England 1216\u20131485|year=1995|publisher=Routledge|location=London|isbn=978-1-31787-323-5|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Wolffe|first=B. P.|title=Henry VI|series=Yale English Monarchs|year=1981|publisher=Yale University Press|location=Berkeley|isbn=978-0-30008-926-4|ref=harv}}\n{{colend}}\n\n{{Wars of the Roses}}\n\n{{featured article}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bonville, William, 1st Baron Bonville}}\n[[Category:1392 births]]\n[[Category:1461 deaths]]\n[[Category:15th-century English people]]\n[[Category:Barons in the Peerage of England]]\n[[Category:English politicians convicted of crimes]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Devon]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Garter]]\n[[Category:People executed under the Lancastrians]]\n[[Category:People executed under the Plantagenets by decapitation]]\n[[Category:People from Devon]]\n[[Category:People of the Hundred Years' War]]\n[[Category:People of the Wars of the Roses]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript| Cleaned up usingAutoEd", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Bonville,_1st_Baron_Bonville"}
{"title_page": "2017 Fresno shooting spree", "text_new": "{{About|a shooting spree in April 2017|the mass shooting in November 2019|2019 Fresno shooting}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title            = 2017 Fresno shooting spree\n| partof           = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| map              = \n| map_size         = \n| map_alt          = \n| map_caption      = \n| location         = {{nowrap|[[Fresno, California]], United States}}\n| target           = \n| coordinates      = \n| date             = April 13/18, 2017\n| time-begin       = {{circa}} 10:45 a.m.\n| time-end         = c. 10:49 a.m.\n| timezone         = [[Pacific Daylight Time|PDT]]\n| type             = [[Shooting spree]]\n| fatalities       = 4\n| injuries         = \n| accused          = Kori Ali Muhammad\n| weapons          = [[.357 Magnum]] [[revolver]]\n| motive           = {{ubl|[[white people|Anti-white]] [[racism]]<ref name=\"abc30:1\">{{cite web|last1=Hoggard|first1=Corin|url=https://abc30.com/5998434/|title=Racial murder motivation part of chilling confession from quad killer|newspaper=[[KFSN-TV]], ABC30|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref name=yourcentralvalley4>{{cite web|last1=Lei Lani|first1=Angelica|url=https://www.yourcentralvalley.com/news/i-wanted-to-kill-them-yes-kori-muhammad-takes-the-stand-in-murder-trial/|title=\u2018I wanted to kill them, yes\u2019: Kori Muhammad takes the stand in murder trial|newspaper=yourcentralvalley , [[KGPE]]|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"KCRA2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kcra.com/article/fresno-shootings-woman-wont-be-charged-in-guards-death/9660774|title=Fresno shootings: Woman won't be charged in guard's death|newspaper=[[KCRA-TV]]|date=May 16, 2017|accessdate=February 11, 2020}}</ref><ref name=fresnobee1>{{cite web|last1=Rodriguez|first1=Robert|url=https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/article241039066.html|title=Confession played in court: Accused killer Kori Muhammad says he wanted to kill white men|newspaper=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>||[[Racial hatred]]}}\n}}\nThe '''[[shooting spree]] in [[Fresno, California]] on April 18, 2017''' was a racially charged shooting spree in which three white men were killed.<ref name=bbc1>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-39636104|title=California gunman kills three 'in race attack' in Fresno|newspaper=[[BBC News]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref><ref name=yourcentralvalley3>{{cite web|last1=Lei Lani|first1=Angelica|url=https://www.yourcentralvalley.com/news/crime/smiling-laughing-and-a-fist-bump-muhammad-trial-includes-autopsies-and-interview-video-2/|title=Smiling, laughing, and a fist-bump: Muhammad trial includes autopsies and interview video|newspaper=yourcentralvalley , [[KGPE]]|date=March 10, 2020|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> Kori Ali Muhammad was the perpetrator and was arrested by police at the scene of his last killing. Muhammad said he went on his shooting spree because of his hatred for [[white people]] and particularly white men.<ref name=\"abc30:1\">{{cite web|last1=Hoggard|first1=Corin|url=https://abc30.com/5998434/|title=Racial murder motivation part of chilling confession from quad killer|newspaper=[[KFSN-TV]], ABC30|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref name=yourcentralvalley4>{{cite web|last1=Lei Lani|first1=Angelica|url=https://www.yourcentralvalley.com/news/i-wanted-to-kill-them-yes-kori-muhammad-takes-the-stand-in-murder-trial/|title=\u2018I wanted to kill them, yes\u2019: Kori Muhammad takes the stand in murder trial|newspaper=yourcentralvalley , [[KGPE]]|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"KCRA2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kcra.com/article/fresno-shootings-woman-wont-be-charged-in-guards-death/9660774|title=Fresno shootings: Woman won't be charged in guard's death|newspaper=[[KCRA-TV]]|date=May 16, 2017|accessdate=February 11, 2020}}</ref><ref name=fresnobee1>{{cite web|last1=Rodriguez|first1=Robert|url=https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/article241039066.html|title=Confession played in court: Accused killer Kori Muhammad says he wanted to kill white men|newspaper=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> Muhammad fired off 17 shots, shooting and killing three men, shooting and missing at another three men, and shooting at a vehicle with passengers inside.The passengers of the vehicle were unharmed. All of Muhammad's victims were white.<ref name=foxnews1>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/fresno-rampage-suspects-timeline-of-alleged-crime-spree-included-3-days-of-voodoo|title=Fresno rampage suspect's timeline of alleged crime spree included 3 days of voodoo|newspaper=[[Fox News]]|date=April 20, 2017|accessdate=February 16, 2020}}</ref> Kori Muhammad was charged with four counts of [[murder]] and four counts of attempted murder.<ref name=yourcentralvalley1>{{cite web|last1=Lei Lani|first1=Angelica|url=https://www.yourcentralvalley.com/news/mother-of-shooting-victim-speaks-as-jury-selection-for-alleged-killers-trial-begins/|title=Mother of shooting victim speaks as jury selection for alleged killer\u2019s trial begins|newspaper=[[KGPE]]|date=February 4, 2020|accessdate=February 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nPrior to Muhammad engaging in the shooting spree, Muhammad shot a security guard dead at a [[Motel 6]] on April 13.<ref name=\"fresnobee6\">{{cite web|last1=Appleton|first1=Rory|last2=Benjamin|first2=Marc|url=http://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/crime/article145499739.html|title=Dyer: Rampage shooter is \u2018calloused\u2019 racist who \u2018set out to kill as many as he could\u2019|newspaper=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=April 19, 2017|accessdate=April 20, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"abc30:1\">{{cite web|last1=Hoggard|first1=Corin|url=https://abc30.com/5998434/|title=Racial murder motivation part of chilling confession from quad killer|newspaper=[[KFSN-TV]], ABC30|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> On his social media posts, police stated that Muhammad made posts of him hating white people and expressing anti- government views.<ref name=\"bbc1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-39636104|title=California gunman kills three 'in race attack' in Fresno|newspaper=[[BBC News]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> Muhammad shouted \"God is greatest\" in Arabic when he was apprehended, however police determined that the crime was not due to religious extremism and was a [[hate crime]]. Muhammad was not affiliated with any terrorist groups.<ref name=\"bbc1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-39636104|title=California gunman kills three 'in race attack' in Fresno|newspaper=[[BBC News]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> \n==Timeline of events==\n\n===Motel 6 shooting===\nAt about 11:00&nbsp;p.m. on April 13, an unarmed security guard working at a [[Motel 6]] in central Fresno observed a man, Kori Ali Muhammad, visiting a woman who had checked into one of the rooms. Since motel policy mandated all visitors to provide identification at the office, the guard went to the room, with an armed coworker, to inform the pair of this. As the guard was escorting the two to the motel office, an argument erupted between the guard and the woman. Muhammad then pulled out a handgun and fired multiple rounds, killing the guard at close range. The guard was identified as Carl Williams. Muhammad also fired several shots toward the motel and at another security guard before fleeing. That guard was uninjured.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Guy|first1=Jim|url=http://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/crime/article144590374.html|title=Unarmed guard, 25, dies in Fresno Motel 6 shooting|newspaper=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=April 14, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref><ref name=fresnobee6>{{cite web|last1=Appleton|first1=Rory|last2=Benjamin|first2=Marc|url=http://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/crime/article145499739.html|title=Dyer: Rampage shooter is \u2018calloused\u2019 racist who \u2018set out to kill as many as he could\u2019|newspaper=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=April 19, 2017|accessdate=April 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Jacobo|first1=Julia|last2=Stone|first2=Alex|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/suspect-fresno-shooting-rampage-charged-previous-murder-motel/story?id=46925155|title=Suspect in Fresno shooting rampage charged with previous murder of motel security guard|newspaper=[[ABC News]]|date=April 20, 2017|accessdate=April 20, 2017}}</ref><ref name=latimes4>{{cite web|last1=Rocha|first1=Veronica|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-kori-muhammad-charged-williams-20170421-story.html|title=Fresno shooting suspect's mental competency to be evaluated|newspaper=[[The Los Angeles Times]]|date=April 21, 2017|accessdate=April 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Manhunt===\nThe woman, who had fled back to the room, was taken into custody on a felony accessory charge after attempting to take evidence from the crime scene and refusing to identify the gunman to police.<ref name=fresnobee5>{{cite web|last1=Lopez|first1=Pablo|url=http://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/crime/article145750649.html|title=Bee exclusive: Affidavit tells how acquaintance of rampage shooter helped him escape motel killing|newspaper=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=April 20, 2017|accessdate=April 20, 2017}}</ref> According to investigators, the gunman escaped police detection at the motel by fleeing south to a nearby [[7-Eleven]] and hiding out on the store rooftop, where he watched officers interview witnesses and waited for them to leave. Once they did the next morning, he got off the rooftop, went to a nearby elementary school, and hid by a dumpster. He then traveled around Fresno over the weekend, changing his appearance by cutting his hair.<ref name=fresnobee6/><ref name=latimes4/>\n\nOn April 18, Fresno police identified one suspect in the shooting, 39-year-old Kori Ali Muhammad (see [[#Suspect|below]]).<ref name=fresnobee2>{{cite web|last1=Guy|first1=Jim|url=http://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/crime/article145212769.html|title=Kori Ali Muhammad also suspected in Motel 6 slaying|newspaper=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> He was a friend of the daughter of the woman at the hotel.<ref name=fresnobee5/> On the same morning, Muhammad went to a [[Starbucks]] coffee shop while out to purchase items for use in voodoo rituals. He used the shop's [[Wi-Fi]] to watch a broadcast by Fresno [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] affiliate [[KFSN-TV]], which identified him as a suspect in the security guard's murder.<ref name=abcnews3>{{cite web|last1=Jacobo|first1=Julia|last2=Stone|first2=Alex|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/fresno-police-chief-releases-details-hate-crime-shooting/story?id=46884877|title=Fresno police chief releases new details in 'hate crime' shooting rampage that killed 3|newspaper=[[ABC News]]|date=April 19, 2017|accessdate=April 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Downtown shootings===\nAfter being identified as a suspect in William's murder, Muhammad decided that he would not \"go down for one murder\" and that he \"might as well take out as many white men\" as he could.<ref name=yourcentralvalley:5/> Hours after the identification, several shootings were reported in downtown Fresno. Muhammad, first approached a [[Pacific Gas and Electric Company]] (PG&E) utility truck at about 10:45&nbsp;a.m. and fired four shots into it, critically wounding an employee seated in the passenger seat. The passenger of the vehicle was identified to be Zachary Randalls.<ref name=fresnobee>{{cite web|last1=Rodriguez|first1=Robert|url=https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/article240845736.html|title=Witness says alleged mass shooter Kori Muhammad had \u2018cold\u2019 look during killing|newspaper=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=March 3, 2020|accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref> The driver of that truck was spared from being shot, since he was deemed Hispanic and thus non white by Muhammad. The driver managed to drive away unharmed, and took Randalls to the [[Fresno Police Department]] headquarters, where he alerted officers. Randalls was taken to [[Community Regional Medical Center]], where he later died.<ref name=fresnobee6/><ref name=fresnobee3>{{cite web|last1=Guy|first1=Jim|url=http://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/crime/article145234709.html|title=Three dead in Fresno shooting rampage; suspected gunman linked to killing of motel guard|newspaper=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref><ref name=kabc1>{{cite web|url=http://abc7.com/news/fresno-triple-shooting-leaves-2-dead;-gunman-at-large/1888575/|title=Fresno Triple Shooting a Hate Crime, Not Act of Terrorism, Police Say|newspaper=[[KABC-TV]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref><ref name=abcnews1>{{cite web|last1=Smith|first1=Scott|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/killed-hurt-shooting-downtown-fresno-california-46870435|title=Fresno shooter wanted to kill many white people, police say|newspaper=[[ABC News]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Pope|first1=Troy|url=http://www.yourcentralvalley.com/news/fresno-police-seek-man-with-shooting-spree-murder-weapon/694537449|title=Fresno police seek man with shooting spree murder weapon|newspaper=Your Central Valley|date=April 19, 2017|accessdate=April 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn Muhammad's murder trial, the driver of the PG&E utility truck testified that the truck was in park when Muhammad approached them sitting in it. From Muhammad's facial expression, the driver said Muhammad had a \"cold, dark look\" which was unnerving. The driver nodded to Muhammad as a gesture from his window, to which Muhammad was unresponsive. Muhammad walked past the drivers left fender and then stopped,  looking into the truck again. The driver told Randalls that he was suspicious of Muhammad's behavior at this moment. As Muhammad reached into his jacket the driver immediately put the truck in reverse. Muhammad fired his gun a few times at the passengers side at Randalls as the driver was backing up. As he backed up a sufficient distance from Muhammad, Muhammad fired off one last shot which hit the head rest of Randall's seat. Randalls told the driver that he was shot. The driver called [[9-1-1]] emergency and drove to the police station because he didn't know where the closest hospital was.<ref name=\"fresnobee\">{{cite web|last1=Rodriguez|first1=Robert|url=https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/article240845736.html|title=Witness says alleged mass shooter Kori Muhammad had \u2018cold\u2019 look during killing|newspaper=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=March 3, 2020|accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref> The driver stated that Randalls lost consciousness on the way to the police station.<ref name=yourcentralvalley2>{{cite web|last1=Lei Lani|first1=Angelica|url=https://www.yourcentralvalley.com/news/accused-spree-killer-kori-muhammad-leaves-during-court-as-witnesses-and-victims-testified-in-his-trial/|title=Accused spree-killer Kori Muhammad leaves during court as witnesses and victims testify in his trial|newspaper=yourcentralvalley , [[KGPE]]|date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=March 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSeconds after shooting four rounds into the PG&E truck on N. Van Ness, Muhammad proceeded south to Mildreda turning west. Kori Muhammad fired two more shots at a 59-year-old man coming out of his house, but missed. The second shot hit a residential dwelling on the other side of the street.<ref name=fresnobee6/> Then Muhammad reloaded his revolver in the alley between Van Ness and Fulton. Muhammad stated he thought about pursuing the 59-year-old man believing he had gone back inside his house but changed his mind. Muhammad then turned onto N Fulton St heading south, where he fired once at a vehicle containing a woman, her adult daughter, and her four-year-old granddaughter, but stopped shooting after realizing they were [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Latino]]. No one in the vehicle suffered any gunshot wounds.<ref name=fresnobee6/><ref name=abcnews3/><ref name=cnn2/><ref name=portlandpress>{{cite web|last1=Smith|first1=Scott|url=http://www.pressherald.com/2017/04/18/police-say-man-who-shot-and-killed-three-shouted-god-is-great-in-arabic/|title=Triple killer in Fresno motivated by hate, not terrorism, police say|newspaper=[[Portland Press Herald]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nMuhammad then walked down the opposite direction, where he spotted a man, Mark Gassett, walking out of a [[Catholic Charities USA]] building. He shot Gassett once in the chest, then killed him with two more shots after he had fallen to the ground.<ref name=\"fresnobee:1\">{{cite web|last1=George|first1=Carmen|last2=Benjamin|first2=Marc|url=https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/crime/article145569374.html|title=\u2018The racism needs to stop,\u2019 says family of shooting victim Mark Gassett, killed walking home with groceries|newspaper=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=April 19, 2017|accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"abc30:3\">{{cite web|last1=Hoggard|first1=Corin|url=https://abc30.com/1888358/|title=Gunman targeting white men kills 3, Fresno Police Chief says; 1 victim identified|newspaper=[[KFSN-TV]], ABC30|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Muhammad then reloaded at a bus stop and fired at three white men. Two of them escaped unharmed, but Muhammad chased the third man, David Jackson.<ref name=\"CNN:2\">{{cite web|last1=Yan|first1=Holly|url=https://www.cnn.com/2017/04/19/us/fresno-shooting-rampage-timeline/index.html|title=Fresno rampage suspect details each day of killing spree to police|newspaper=[[CNN]]|date=April 19, 2017|accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref> Jackson, who was the heaviest and oldest, was followed into the parking lot of a [[Catholic Charities USA]] building. There Muhammad fired six shots: two that killed the Jackson, two that struck parked vehicles, one that struck a nearby building, and a sixth that has yet to be recovered. Witnesses said that Muhammad cursed as he fired.<ref name=fresnobee6/><ref name=abcnews3/><ref name=fresnobee3/><ref name=time1>{{cite web|last1=Smith|first1=Scott|last2=Bollag|first2=Sophia|url=http://time.com/4747423/fresno-shooting-kori-ali-muhammad/|title=Fresno Shooting Suspect Laughed About the Killings in Police Interviews|newspaper=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=April 19, 2017|accessdate=April 19, 2017}}</ref><ref name=cnn2>{{cite web|last1=Hanna|first1=Jason|last2=Mossburg|first2=Cheri|last3=Simon|first3=Darran|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/04/19/us/fresno-shootings-hate-crime/|title=Fresno shooting: Rampage started with slaying last week, police say|newspaper=[[CNN]]|date=April 19, 2017|accessdate=April 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOfficers responding to [[shotspotter]] reports found Muhammad running down the street, and managed to arrest him.<ref name=fresnobee3/> During the arrest, Muhammad shouted, \"''[[Takbir|Allahu Akbar]]''!\"<ref name=newsweek1/> Several bullets and [[speedloader]]s for a [[.357 Magnum]] revolver were recovered from his person, but no firearm was found.<ref name=fresnobee3/> According to Chief Jerry Dyer, the gun was wrapped in clothing and picked up by a [[Hispanic]] male who had met up with Muhammad shortly after the shootings and then fled the scene.<ref name=fresnobee6/><ref name=abcnews3/> Dyer also said a total of seventeen shots were fired in 90 seconds during these shootings.<ref name=abcnews3/><ref name=bbc1>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-39636104|title=California gunman kills three 'in race attack' in Fresno|newspaper=[[BBC News]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref><ref name=latimes1>{{cite web|last1=Rocha|first1=Veronica|last2=Serna|first2=Joseph|last3=Marcum|first3=Diana|last4=Branson-Potts|first4=Hailey|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-fresno-shooting-20170418-story.html|title=Hate crime is suspected after a gunman kills 3 white men in downtown Fresno|newspaper=[[The Los Angeles Times]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> Four minutes had passed between the first shots and Muhammad's arrest.<ref name=fresnobee6/> Several streets and county government buildings were put on [[lockdown]] during the shootings, with people being ordered to [[shelter in place]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.turnto23.com/news/state/2-dead-1-injured-in-fresno-shooting|title=3 dead in 3 different locations in Fresno shooting|newspaper=[[KERO-TV]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Whitcomb|first1=Dan|last2=Gorman|first2=Steve|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-california-shooting-idUSKBN17K2DJ|title=Gunman targeting white men kills 3 in Fresno, California|newspaper=[[Reuters]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] and [[Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives|ATF]] were notified of the shootings.<ref name=fresnobee3/> Agents from the [[United States Department of Homeland Security|Department of Homeland Security]] also responded to the Fresno Police Department headquarters.<ref name=newsweek1>{{cite web|last1=Le Miere|first1=Jason|url=http://www.newsweek.com/kori-ali-muhammad-fresno-shootiung-585806|title=In Fresno Shooting, Suspect Kori Ali Muhammad Shouted 'Allahu Akbar,' Wrote About Hatred of White People|newspaper=[[Newsweek]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> Chief Dyer said that the incident was \"a random act of violence\" and that the gunman acted alone, adding that it was \"too soon\" to determine whether the shootings were acts of terrorism.<ref name=fresnobee3/> A federal law enforcement official said the shootings did not bear the hallmarks of a terrorist attack and appeared to be more of a \"local, criminal matter\".<ref name=washingtonpost1>{{cite web|last1=Berman|first1=Mark|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-nation/wp/2017/04/18/3-people-killed-during-unprovoked-shooting-rampage-in-fresno-police-say/|title=Three people killed in \u2018unprovoked\u2019 Fresno shooting rampage \u2018motivated by hate,\u2019 police say|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nLocal authorities said they would investigate the shootings as a [[hate crime]].<ref name=latimes1/> Chief Dyer said that Kori Muhammad, who is [[Black people|black]], told police he decided to become infamous for killing many white people after realizing he was wanted in the Motel 6 shooting.<ref name=portlandpress/><ref name=wboc>{{cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/35180183/the-latest-police-say-fresno-man-shot-3-after-being-ided|title=The Latest: Brother of Fresno suspect shocked by killings|newspaper=[[WBOC-TV]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419193128/http://www.wboc.com/story/35180183/the-latest-police-say-fresno-man-shot-3-after-being-ided|archive-date=April 19, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=mercurynews>{{cite web|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/2017/04/18/the-latest-3-shot-killed-in-california-suspect-caught/|title=The Latest: Brother of Fresno suspect shocked by killings|newspaper=[[The Mercury News]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> Muhammad led investigators through the murder scenes and described exactly how he committed the shooting rampage, laughing all the while.<ref name=abcnews3/><ref name=yourcentralvalley3>{{cite web|last1=Lei Lani|first1=Angelica|url=https://www.yourcentralvalley.com/news/crime/smiling-laughing-and-a-fist-bump-muhammad-trial-includes-autopsies-and-interview-video-2/|title=Smiling, laughing, and a fist-bump: Muhammad trial includes autopsies and interview video|newspaper=yourcentralvalley , [[KGPE]]|date=March 10, 2020|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAll of the victims killed in the shootings were white males.<ref name=washingtonpost1/> The Motel 6 security guard was identified as 25-year-old Carl Williams.<ref name=fresnobee2/> The victims of the April 18 shootings were identified the next day as PG&E employee Zackary David Randalls, 34, of [[Clovis, California|Clovis]]; and Mark James Gassett, 37, and David Martin Jackson, 58, both of Fresno.<ref name=abcnews3/><ref name=nbcnews2>{{cite web|last1=Johnson|first1=Alex|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/fresno-gunman-targeted-many-white-males-possible-cops-say-n748566|title=Fresno Gunman Targeted \u2018as Many White Males as Possible,\u2019 Cops Say|newspaper=[[NBC News]]|date=April 19, 2017|accessdate=April 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nMayor [[Lee Brand]] offered his condolences to the victims' families and called April 18 \"a sad day for us all\".<ref name=washingtonpost1/> PG&E expressed its own condolences to all those involved, including the family of the slain employee.<ref name=latimes1/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Pope|first1=Troy|url=http://www.yourcentralvalley.com/news/suspect-in-fresno-shooting-spree-that-killed-3-shouts-allahu-akbar-when-arrested/693838151|title=Suspect in Fresno shooting spree that killed 3 shouts 'Allahu Akbar' when arrested|newspaper=Your Central Valley|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Perpetrator==\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Kori Ali Muhammad\n| image = \n| image_upright = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| alias = Kori McDonald<ref name=abcnews3/><br>Kori MacSon McWallace<ref name=fresnobee4/><br>B-God MacSun\n| birth_name = Cory Allen Taylor\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1978|3|21}}<ref name=cbi>{{cite web|url=http://www.californiabirthindex.org/birth/cory_allen_taylor_born_1978_13842834 |title=Cory Allen Taylor |publisher=California Birth Index |accessdate=April 19, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419193351/http://www.californiabirthindex.org/birth/cory_allen_taylor_born_1978_13842834 |archivedate=April 19, 2017 }}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Fresno County]], California \n| residence = \n| education = [[American River College]]<br>[[Cosumnes River College]]<br>[[Fresno City College]]<br>[[Sacramento City College]]\n| nationality = American\n| children = 3\n}}\nKori Ali Muhammad (born March 21, 1978) was identified as the prime suspect in all of the shootings. He was homeless at the time,<ref name=fresnobee2/> and had some association with gangs, but wasn't a member of one himself.<ref name=washingtonpost1/> He has three children.<ref name=guardian/>\n\n===Personal background===\nBorn as '''Cory Allen Taylor''',<ref name=cbi/> and also previously known as '''Kori Taylor''',<ref name=heavy>{{cite web|last1=McBride|first1=Jessica|url=http://heavy.com/news/2017/04/kori-ali-muhammad-fresno-shooting-isis-allahu-akbar-terror-attack-photos-facebook-suspect-california/|title=Kori Ali Muhammad: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know|newspaper=[[Heavy.com]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> Muhammad changed his name to his present one as a teenager.<ref name=latimes2>{{cite web|last1=Serna|first1=Joseph|last2=Branson-Potts|first2=Hailey|last3=Queally|first3=James|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-fresno-shooter-suspect-20170418-story.html|title=Suspect in Fresno shooting rampage spoke about racial conflict and black nationalism|newspaper=[[The Los Angeles Times]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> His grandmother said that Muhammad had been drawn to [[Islam]] at a young age. Muhammad's aunt said that her nephew also attended a [[Baptists|Baptist]] church when he was younger.<ref name=guardian>{{cite web|last1=Levin|first1=Sam|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/apr/19/fresno-shooting-hate-crime-kori-ali-muhammad|title=Fresno shooting decried as anti-white hate crime, but truth is complicated|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=April 19, 2017|accessdate=April 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nMuhammad was a resident of both Fresno and [[Sacramento, California]]. According to Muhammad's [[Facebook]] page, he studied [[multimedia]] at [[Cosumnes River College]] in Sacramento. A spokesman for the [[Los Rios Community College District]] identified a student named Kori McWallace\u2014with the same date of birth as Muhammad\u2014who attended Cosumnes, [[American River College]], and [[Sacramento City College]] at various times from 1996 to 2004. However, no details were immediately offered about his studies or if he graduated.<ref name=sacbee1>{{cite web|last1=Stanton|first1=Sam|last2=Lambert|first2=Diana|url=http://www.sacbee.com/news/local/crime/article145324594.html|title=Suspect in Fresno slayings had ties to Sacramento, including a felony rap sheet|newspaper=[[The Sacramento Bee]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> Muhammad also attended classes at [[Fresno City College]], but according to a classmate, he would often not show up for weeks at a time and accuse his instructors of being racist.<ref name=bbc1/>\n\n===Previous criminal history===\nMuhammad had a criminal history dated from 1997 to 2004, consisting of arrests on weapons, drugs, forgery, and false imprisonment charges, as well as making terrorist threats.<ref name=abcnews1/><ref name=mercurynews/> Court documents also indicated that he \"suffered auditory hallucinations and had at least two prior mental health hospitalizations.\"<ref name=wboc/> Two of his earliest arrests occurred when he was still a teenager; on both occasions, he allegedly brought a gun to school. In 2004, Muhammad was arrested in [[Washington (state)|Washington state]] for allegedly firing a gun outside his apartment. He left the state and the case was dismissed after prosecutors declined to extradite him to a federal prison.<ref name=cbsnews3>{{cite web|url=http://cbsnews.com/amp/news/fresno-shooting-spree-suspect-had-criminal-history-said-he-joined-gang-at-9/|title=Fresno shooting spree suspect had criminal history, said he joined gang at 9|newspaper=[[CBS News]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=April 20, 2017|accessdate=April 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAccording to court records filed in February 2005, he was arrested and indicted in federal court on charges of \"possession of cocaine with intent to distribute, possession of a firearm for drug trafficking and possession of a firearm by a convicted felon\".<ref name=latimes1/> In September, Muhammad sought an insanity defense and underwent a psychiatric evaluation after his lawyer claimed his client was \"suffering from hallucinations, paranoia and psychosis.\"<ref name=sacbee1/><ref name=latimes3>{{cite web|url=http://documents.latimes.com/judge-commits-accused-fresno-shooter-facility-because-he-was-mental-health-issues/|title=Criminal history of accused Fresno shooter Kori Ali Muhammad: Committed to mental health facility|newspaper=[[The Los Angeles Times]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> A judge ruled that he was incompetent to stand trial and had him committed to a facility for up to four months.<ref name=latimes3/> He was deemed competent in August 2006, after which he pleaded guilty to two of seven counts in the indictment. Muhammad was sentenced to over nine years in prison, though the sentence was downgraded to over seven years in 2008. He was released from prison early in September 2016.<ref name=latimes1/><ref name=heavy/><ref name=sacbee1/>\n\nMuhammad claimed to have shot a person at the age of twelve, but the claim was not confirmed by police.<ref name=fresnobee6/>\n\n===Views and statements===\nMuhammad maintained two Facebook profiles and a [[Twitter]] account,<ref name=fresnobee4>{{cite web|last1=Appleton|first1=Rory|url=http://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/crime/article145293959.html|title=Suspected Fresno rampage killer may have threatened Trump on social media|newspaper=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> all in which he paid homage to [[black pride]] and [[black nationalism]]. His profile depicted images of a [[Black Power]] [[Raised fist|salute]] and [[Pan-African flag|a flag]] associated with the [[Pan-Africanism]] movement.<ref name=latimes2/> According to police, he \"expressed hatred of whites\" and the government.<ref name=fresnobee3/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2017/04/18/fresno-shooting-spree-3-people-killed-suspect-in-custody.html|title=Fresno shooting rampage: Suspect who shot dead 3 wanted to kill as many people as possible, police say|newspaper=[[FOX News]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> Muhammad made posts about [[2016 shooting of Dallas police officers|the murders of five Dallas police officers]], in which he praised the shooter Micah Xavier Johnson.<ref name=heavy/> He also consistently used the [[hashtag]] \"#LetBlackPeopleGo\" and encouraged \"black warriors\" to \"mount up\".<ref name=time1/> Muhammad's father described his son's belief that there was an ongoing war between whites and blacks, and that \"a battle was about to take place.\"<ref name=latimes1/> He later said that he attempted to warn Muhammad's probation officer about his son's hatred of white people and his plans of killing them, but believes no one followed up on his report.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hoggard|first1=Corin|url=http://abc30.com/news/father-of-fresno-shooting-spree-suspect-talks-about-son/1893733/|title=Father of Fresno Shooting Spree Suspect Talks About Son|newspaper=[[KFSN-TV]]|date=April 19, 2017|accessdate=April 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn a phone interview with an ABC News affiliate in downtown Fresno Jail, Kori Ali Muhammad spoke about his motives for the killings. Muhammad spoke about his hatred for [[white people]] and especially white men. Muhammad stated that \"someone has to fight for them. Someone has to fight for all the people that died at the hands of racist white men.\" \nMuhammad was initially wanted by [[Fresno]] police for the death of Carl Williams, a security guard he killed a few days before his shooting spree. Muhammad added that \"I was actually going to turn myself in.Then I started thinking about the missing black women and children... started thinking about Flint Michigan...starting thinking about the crack cocaine epidemic...started thinking about all the injustices and atrocities that my people go through. That's why I snapped. I wasn't thinking like I'm going to kill, kill, kill, all I know was that white supremacy has to die and people that benefit most from white supremacy are white men.\"\nMuhammad believed himself to be a martyr saying \"I gave my life for the freedom of people. The ultimate freedom of my people.\"<ref name=KCRA2>{{cite web|url=https://www.kcra.com/article/fresno-shootings-woman-wont-be-charged-in-guards-death/9660774|title=Fresno shootings: Woman won't be charged in guard's death|newspaper=[[KCRA-TV]]|date=May 16, 2017|accessdate=February 11, 2020}}</ref>\nMuhammad stated that \u201cConsidering the crime I did, I can live with having to be in jail, like I know what I did was wrong.\u201d When asked if he regretted killing four people Muhammad stated that he did not.<ref name=yourcentralvalley>{{cite web|last1=Lei Lani|first1=Angelica|url=https://www.yourcentralvalley.com/news/crime/would-you-rather-i-be-dead-muhammad-trial-hears-calls-he-made-to-his-mother-after-his-arrest/|title=\u2018Would you rather I be dead?\u2019; Muhammad trial hears calls he made to his mother after his arrest|newspaper=yourcentralvalley , [[KGPE]]|date=March 11, 2020|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn Muhammad's [[capital punishment]] trial, Muhammad chose to testify and answer questions about his killing spree. When asked if he intended to kill a white man, Zachary Randalls in the [[PG&E]] truck, Muhammad stated that \"I wanted to kill them, yes\". Muhammad kept alluding to his own version of ancient [[religious]] prophesies. Muhammad stated that \u201cGod is going to destroy white men in particular, specifically. It was written and 25,000 years ago that this had to happen.\u201d Muhammad also compared his killings to the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|coronavirus]], stating that he shot Mark Gassett when he was on the ground to make sure he was dead. Muhammad stated \"I wanted to kill him, just like the coronavirus is killing white men right now.\"<ref name=yourcentralvalley4>{{cite web|last1=Lei Lani|first1=Angelica|url=https://www.yourcentralvalley.com/news/i-wanted-to-kill-them-yes-kori-muhammad-takes-the-stand-in-murder-trial/|title=\u2018I wanted to kill them, yes\u2019: Kori Muhammad takes the stand in murder trial|newspaper=yourcentralvalley , [[KGPE]]|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring testimony, Muhammad claimed he was a god, and stated that God would destroy America if African-Americans were not given reparations. He also claimed to take credit for the destruction of [[Paradise, California]] during the 2018 [[Camp Fire (2018)]].<ref name=yourcentralvalley:5/>\n\n\n\nAccording to ''[[The Daily Beast]]'', Muhammad's posts indicated a support of the [[Moorish Science Temple of America]], an [[African Americans|African American]] organization associated with the [[sovereign citizen movement]], which advocated few beliefs similar to those of mainstream [[Islam]].<ref name=heavy/> Brian Levin, director of [[California State University, San Bernardino|Cal State San Bernardino]]'s Center for the Study of Hate and Extremism, said that Muhammad's social media posts made multiple references to terms used by the [[Nation of Islam]] (NOI),<ref name=latimes2/> a [[black supremacist]] organization labeled as a [[hate group]] by the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]] and the [[Anti-Defamation League]].<ref name=\"SPLC:1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.splcenter.org/fighting-hate/extremist-files/group/nation-islam|title=Nation of Islam|publisher=[[Southern Poverty Law Center]]|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ADL:1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/resources/profiles/the-nation-of-islam|title=The Nation of Islam|publisher=[[Anti-Defamation League]]|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref> Muhammad made references to \"grafted white devils\", an expression frequently used in the Nation of Islam to describe [[white people]], and \"Yakub\", the villainous figure responsible for creating white people in the Nation of Islam.<ref name=latimes2/><ref name=\"SPLC:2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.splcenter.org/hatewatch/2017/04/19/possible-black-separatist-kori-ali-muhammad-kills-three-fresno|title=Possible Black Separatist Kori Ali Muhammad Kills Three in Fresno|newspaper=[[Southern Poverty Law Center]]|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref> \nMuhammad said he drew inspiration from [[Wallace Fard Muhammad]], an important figure in the Nation of Islam.<ref name=\"fox23\">{{cite web|last1=Lehnert|first1=Alexandra|url=https://kmph.com/news/local/learning-more-about-kori-muhammad|title=Learning more about Kori Muhammad|newspaper=[[KMPH-TV]]|date=April 20, 2017|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref name=latimes1/> Muhammad's relatives said that he \"became involved\" with the NOI when he was younger, but did not clarify what kind of role the group played in his life during his imprisonment and after his release.<ref name=guardian/>\n\nMuhammad's beliefs included a mixture of the Nation of Islam and also [[voodoo]] which he said is called Kali Sufi. He used amulets and necklaces for his voodoo religion, and referred to himself as a god.<ref name=\"abc30:I am a god\">{{cite web|last1=Hoggard|first1=Corin|url=https://abc30.com/kori-muhammad-admits-to-killing-4-people/6022284/|title='I am a god': Fresno mass shooting suspect Kori Muhammad admits to killing 4 people|newspaper=[[KFSN-TV]], ABC30|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February, Muhammad released two [[hip-hop]] albums on [[iTunes]] and [[YouTube]] under the name of '''B-God MacSun'''. ''[[The Los Angeles Times]]'' noted that Muhammad sang that he was an \"[[Asia]]tic black god\", and that the album's contents \"repeatedly references violence between black and white people.\"<ref name=latimes1/><ref name=fresnobee4/><ref name=latimes2/>\n\nIn addition, Muhammad produced a music-themed talk show at the Community Media Access Collaborative, a [[nonprofit organization]] specializing in promoting people and companies through the use of media. Muhammad's talk show ran for four episodes, which were produced between May 12, 2015, and October 10, 2016.<ref name=fresnobee4/> In that talk show, he claimed that he had joined a Sacramento gang at the age of nine, the \"black liberation movement\" at the age of fourteen, and the NOI later on in his teens.<ref name=cbsnews3/> The organization's director of operations described Muhammad, a frequenter at the facility, as \"kind and curious\" to the staff.<ref name=fresnobee4/> However, a former friend who met Muhammad at the facility, but later removed him from his [[Friending and following|friended]] list on Facebook, described him as \"intense and unnerving\"<ref name=nbcnews2/>\n\nAn [[imam]] at a local mosque said that Muhammad was not a member of his congregation.<ref name=washingtonpost1/> Following his arrest, Muhammad affirmed to officers that he is Muslim, but that he had not been to a mosque in 25 years and that he prays to a total of seven different deities.<ref name=time1/> He also told officers that he was not officially affiliated with any terrorist groups.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mays|first1=Mackenzie|last2=Anderson|first2=Barbara|url=http://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/crime/article145629169.html|title=Experts say shooting rampage is a hate crime \u2013 but not an act of terrorism. Here\u2019s why.|newspaper=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=April 19, 2017|accessdate=April 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Legal proceedings==\nFollowing his arrest, Muhammad was charged with four counts of [[murder]] and two counts of assault with a deadly weapon.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mossburg|first1=Cheri|last2=Simon|first2=Darran|last3=Park|first3=Madison|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/04/18/us/fresno-california-shootings/|title=Police chief: Fresno killings a hate crime|newspaper=[[CNN]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> On April 21, he made his first court appearance for the first-degree murder of Carl Williams and the attempted murder of the second security guard at the Motel 6. During the hearing, he shouted on two different occasions, saying \"Let black people go\" and a phrase similar to \"in reparations\" that was not clearly enunciated. He also warned that natural disasters striking the U.S. will increase. As a result, criminal proceedings were suspended and the judge ordered a psychiatric evaluation for Muhammad, setting bail at $2.6 million. Muhammad faces the death penalty if convicted of all four murders.<ref name=latimes4/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Lopez|first1=Pablo|url=http://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/crime/article145958869.html|title=Fresno shooting spree: \u2018Let black people go!\u2019 Kori Muhammad yells in court|newspaper=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=April 21, 2017|accessdate=April 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/latest-fresno-california-gunman-enters-court-shouting-46938448|title=Fresno, California gunman enters court shouting|newspaper=[[ABC News]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=April 21, 2017|accessdate=April 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/newswires/news/national/fresno-killing-suspect-shouts-1st-court-hearing-article-1.3083872|title=Fresno killing suspect shouts out during 1st court hearing|newspaper=[[The New York Daily News]]|date=April 21, 2017|accessdate=April 21, 2017}}</ref> His next court appearance was scheduled on May 12,<ref name=latimes4/> but postponed to June 1 to give psychologists more time to prepare Muhammad's mental health report.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Appleton|first1=Rory|title=Psychologist needs more time to evaluate Fresno shooting suspect\u2019s mental state, judge says|url=http://www.modbee.com/article150158612.html|newspaper=[[The Modesto Bee]]|date=May 12, 2017|accessdate=May 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn October 13, 2017 the judge set a trial date for January 8, 2018. The initial hearings will focus on Muhammad's mental competency. During the hearings Muhammad shouted demands for slavery reparations and also yelled \"Allahu akbar.\" Muhammad's lawyer says he continues to gather evidence that he is incompetent to be held criminally responsible. Two psychiatrists have determined that he is incompetent but another says that he is not.<ref name=\"FresnoTV\">{{cite news|last1=Haagenson|first1=Gene|title=Mental competency trial date set for Fresno shooting spree suspect|url=http://abc30.com/mental-competency-trial-date-set-for-fresno-shooting-spree-suspect/2529165/|accessdate=27 November 2017|publisher=ABC 30 Action News|date=13 October 2017}}</ref> Dr. Meloy declared Muhammad competent and stated that \"He knows the \"shrink talk\". He knows how to communicate to a psychologist or psychiatrist when he's being interviewed because he knows what the psychiatrist or psychologist is looking for.\" Dr Meloy believed that Muhammad's schizophrenia was managed effectively and that it was a non factor in Muhammad's thinking to deduce right from wrong in the killings.<ref name=\"abc30:2\">{{cite web|last1=Rose|first1=Sontaya|url=https://abc30.com/kori-muhammad-an-expert-at-pretending-to-be-delusional-for-his-benefit-da-says/2965961/|title=Kori Muhammad an expert at pretending to be delusional for his benefit, DA says|newspaper=[[KFSN-TV]], ABC30|date=January 19, 2018|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> On January 22, 2018, Judge Jonathan Conklin ruled that Muhammad is competent to stand trial.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lopez|first1=Pablo|url=http://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/crime/article195944044.html|title=Accused Fresno rampage killer is competent to stand trial, judge rules|newspaper=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=January 22, 2018|accessdate=January 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fresnobee.com/news/state/california/article196030899.html|title=California judge: Alleged killer of 4 mentally fit for trial|newspaper=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=January 22, 2018|accessdate=January 23, 2018|website=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180124005809/http://www.fresnobee.com/news/state/california/article196030899.html|archive-date=January 24, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nJury selection for Muhammad's trial began on February 4, 2020<ref name=yourcentralvalley1>{{cite web|last1=Lei Lani|first1=Angelica|url=https://www.yourcentralvalley.com/news/mother-of-shooting-victim-speaks-as-jury-selection-for-alleged-killers-trial-begins/|title=Mother of shooting victim speaks as jury selection for alleged killer\u2019s trial begins|newspaper=[[KGPE]]|date=February 4, 2020|accessdate=February 11, 2020}}</ref> and the trial began on March 2.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/crime/article240813601.html|title=Opening statements heard as the murder trial for Kori Ali Muhammad begins|date=March 2, 2020|website=fresnobee.com}}</ref>  \nMuhammad faces four murder charges and four attempted murder charges. Fresno District Attorney Lisa A. Smittcamp is seeking the [[death penalty]].<ref name=yourcentralvalley1/>\n\nMuhammad testified in court that he shot and killed Carl Williams. He testified that he later went on a shooting spree and shot and killed Zachary Randalls, Mark Gassett, and David Jackson, and shot at three other white men. Muhammad confessed to trying to kill as many white men as he could. When asked why he shot Mark Gassett while he lay on the ground wounded from the previous shots, Muhammad admitted that his intention was \"to kill him, just like the coronavirus is killing white men.\" He made several more references to the [[coronavirus]] when confessing to shooting people at the bus stop.<ref name=yourcentralvalley:5>{{cite web|last1=Pope |first1=Troy|url=https://www.yourcentralvalley.com/news/crime/muhammad-takes-the-stand-in-murder-trial-confesses-to-killing-4-men/|title=Muhammad takes the stand in murder trial, confesses to killing 4 men|newspaper=yourcentralvalley [[KGPE]]|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[2016 shooting of Baton Rouge police officers]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC8WX2lUGdDv9UeVaq6CFvig Kori Ali Muhammad's YouTube channel]\n*[https://www.yourcentralvalley.com/news/crime/muhammad-takes-the-stand-in-murder-trial-confesses-to-killing-4-men/ Kori Ali Muhammad's confession in murder trial]\n*[https://www.docketalarm.com/cases/California_State_Fresno_County_Superior_Court/F17902482/The_People_of_the_State_of_California_vs._Kori_Ali_Muhammad/ The People of the State of California vs. Kori Ali Muhammad]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fresno shooting spree, 2017}}\n[[Category:Spree shootings in the United States]]\n[[Category:2017 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:April 2017 crimes in the United States]]\n[[Category:2017 crimes in California]]\n[[Category:2010s in Fresno, California|2017 shootings]]\n[[Category:Racially motivated violence against European Americans]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|a shooting spree in April 2017|the mass shooting in November 2019|2019 Fresno shooting}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title            = 2017 Fresno shooting spree\n| partof           = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| map              = \n| map_size         = \n| map_alt          = \n| map_caption      = \n| location         = {{nowrap|[[Fresno, California]], United States}}\n| target           = \n| coordinates      = \n| date             = April 13/18, 2017\n| time-begin       = {{circa}} 10:45 a.m.\n| time-end         = c. 10:49 a.m.\n| timezone         = [[Pacific Daylight Time|PDT]]\n| type             = [[Shooting spree]]\n| fatalities       = 4\n| injuries         = \n| accused          = Kori Ali Muhammad\n| weapons          = [[.357 Magnum]] [[revolver]]\n| motive           = {{ubl|[[white people|Anti-white]] [[racism]]<ref name=\"abc30:1\">{{cite web|last1=Hoggard|first1=Corin|url=https://abc30.com/5998434/|title=Racial murder motivation part of chilling confession from quad killer|newspaper=[[KFSN-TV]], ABC30|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref name=yourcentralvalley4>{{cite web|last1=Lei Lani|first1=Angelica|url=https://www.yourcentralvalley.com/news/i-wanted-to-kill-them-yes-kori-muhammad-takes-the-stand-in-murder-trial/|title=\u2018I wanted to kill them, yes\u2019: Kori Muhammad takes the stand in murder trial|newspaper=yourcentralvalley , [[KGPE]]|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"KCRA2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kcra.com/article/fresno-shootings-woman-wont-be-charged-in-guards-death/9660774|title=Fresno shootings: Woman won't be charged in guard's death|newspaper=[[KCRA-TV]]|date=May 16, 2017|accessdate=February 11, 2020}}</ref><ref name=fresnobee1>{{cite web|last1=Rodriguez|first1=Robert|url=https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/article241039066.html|title=Confession played in court: Accused killer Kori Muhammad says he wanted to kill white men|newspaper=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>||[[Racial hatred]]}}\n}}\nThe '''[[shooting spree]] in [[Fresno, California]] on April 18, 2017''' was a racially charged shooting spree in which three white men were killed.<ref name=bbc1>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-39636104|title=California gunman kills three 'in race attack' in Fresno|newspaper=[[BBC News]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref><ref name=yourcentralvalley3>{{cite web|last1=Lei Lani|first1=Angelica|url=https://www.yourcentralvalley.com/news/crime/smiling-laughing-and-a-fist-bump-muhammad-trial-includes-autopsies-and-interview-video-2/|title=Smiling, laughing, and a fist-bump: Muhammad trial includes autopsies and interview video|newspaper=yourcentralvalley , [[KGPE]]|date=March 10, 2020|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> Kori Ali Muhammad was the perpetrator and was arrested by police at the scene of his last killing. Muhammad said he went on his shooting spree because of his hatred for [[white people]] and particularly white men.<ref name=\"abc30:1\">{{cite web|last1=Hoggard|first1=Corin|url=https://abc30.com/5998434/|title=Racial murder motivation part of chilling confession from quad killer|newspaper=[[KFSN-TV]], ABC30|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref name=yourcentralvalley4>{{cite web|last1=Lei Lani|first1=Angelica|url=https://www.yourcentralvalley.com/news/i-wanted-to-kill-them-yes-kori-muhammad-takes-the-stand-in-murder-trial/|title=\u2018I wanted to kill them, yes\u2019: Kori Muhammad takes the stand in murder trial|newspaper=yourcentralvalley , [[KGPE]]|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"KCRA2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kcra.com/article/fresno-shootings-woman-wont-be-charged-in-guards-death/9660774|title=Fresno shootings: Woman won't be charged in guard's death|newspaper=[[KCRA-TV]]|date=May 16, 2017|accessdate=February 11, 2020}}</ref><ref name=fresnobee1>{{cite web|last1=Rodriguez|first1=Robert|url=https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/article241039066.html|title=Confession played in court: Accused killer Kori Muhammad says he wanted to kill white men|newspaper=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> Muhammad fired off 17 shots, shooting and killing three men, shooting and missing at another three men, and shooting at a vehicle with passengers inside.The passengers of the vehicle were unharmed. All of Muhammad's victims were white.<ref name=foxnews1>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/fresno-rampage-suspects-timeline-of-alleged-crime-spree-included-3-days-of-voodoo|title=Fresno rampage suspect's timeline of alleged crime spree included 3 days of voodoo|newspaper=[[Fox News]]|date=April 20, 2017|accessdate=February 16, 2020}}</ref> Kori Muhammad was charged with four counts of [[murder]] and four counts of attempted murder.<ref name=yourcentralvalley1>{{cite web|last1=Lei Lani|first1=Angelica|url=https://www.yourcentralvalley.com/news/mother-of-shooting-victim-speaks-as-jury-selection-for-alleged-killers-trial-begins/|title=Mother of shooting victim speaks as jury selection for alleged killer\u2019s trial begins|newspaper=[[KGPE]]|date=February 4, 2020|accessdate=February 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nPrior to Muhammad engaging in the shooting spree, Muhammad shot a security guard dead at a [[Motel 6]] on April 13.<ref name=\"fresnobee6\">{{cite web|last1=Appleton|first1=Rory|last2=Benjamin|first2=Marc|url=http://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/crime/article145499739.html|title=Dyer: Rampage shooter is \u2018calloused\u2019 racist who \u2018set out to kill as many as he could\u2019|newspaper=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=April 19, 2017|accessdate=April 20, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"abc30:1\">{{cite web|last1=Hoggard|first1=Corin|url=https://abc30.com/5998434/|title=Racial murder motivation part of chilling confession from quad killer|newspaper=[[KFSN-TV]], ABC30|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> On his social media posts, police stated that Muhammad made posts of him hating white people and expressing anti- government views.<ref name=\"bbc1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-39636104|title=California gunman kills three 'in race attack' in Fresno|newspaper=[[BBC News]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> Muhammad shouted \"God is greatest\" in Arabic when he was apprehended, however police determined that the crime was not due to religious extremism and was a [[hate crime]]. Muhammad was not affiliated with any terrorist groups.<ref name=\"bbc1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-39636104|title=California gunman kills three 'in race attack' in Fresno|newspaper=[[BBC News]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> \n==Timeline of events==\n\n===Motel 6 shooting===\nAt about 11:00&nbsp;p.m. on April 13, an unarmed security guard working at a [[Motel 6]] in central Fresno observed a man, Kori Ali Muhammad, visiting a woman who had checked into one of the rooms. Since motel policy mandated all visitors to provide identification at the office, the guard went to the room, with an armed coworker, to inform the pair of this. As the guard was escorting the two to the motel office, an argument erupted between the guard and the woman. Muhammad then pulled out a handgun and fired multiple rounds, killing the guard at close range. The guard was identified as Carl Williams. Muhammad also fired several shots toward the motel and at another security guard before fleeing. That guard was uninjured.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Guy|first1=Jim|url=http://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/crime/article144590374.html|title=Unarmed guard, 25, dies in Fresno Motel 6 shooting|newspaper=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=April 14, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref><ref name=fresnobee6>{{cite web|last1=Appleton|first1=Rory|last2=Benjamin|first2=Marc|url=http://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/crime/article145499739.html|title=Dyer: Rampage shooter is \u2018calloused\u2019 racist who \u2018set out to kill as many as he could\u2019|newspaper=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=April 19, 2017|accessdate=April 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Jacobo|first1=Julia|last2=Stone|first2=Alex|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/suspect-fresno-shooting-rampage-charged-previous-murder-motel/story?id=46925155|title=Suspect in Fresno shooting rampage charged with previous murder of motel security guard|newspaper=[[ABC News]]|date=April 20, 2017|accessdate=April 20, 2017}}</ref><ref name=latimes4>{{cite web|last1=Rocha|first1=Veronica|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-kori-muhammad-charged-williams-20170421-story.html|title=Fresno shooting suspect's mental competency to be evaluated|newspaper=[[The Los Angeles Times]]|date=April 21, 2017|accessdate=April 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Manhunt===\nThe woman, who had fled back to the room, was taken into custody on a felony accessory charge after attempting to take evidence from the crime scene and refusing to identify the gunman to police.<ref name=fresnobee5>{{cite web|last1=Lopez|first1=Pablo|url=http://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/crime/article145750649.html|title=Bee exclusive: Affidavit tells how acquaintance of rampage shooter helped him escape motel killing|newspaper=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=April 20, 2017|accessdate=April 20, 2017}}</ref> According to investigators, the gunman escaped police detection at the motel by fleeing south to a nearby [[7-Eleven]] and hiding out on the store rooftop, where he watched officers interview witnesses and waited for them to leave. Once they did the next morning, he got off the rooftop, went to a nearby elementary school, and hid by a dumpster. He then traveled around Fresno over the weekend, changing his appearance by cutting his hair.<ref name=fresnobee6/><ref name=latimes4/>\n\nOn April 18, Fresno police identified one suspect in the shooting, 39-year-old Kori Ali Muhammad (see [[#Suspect|below]]).<ref name=fresnobee2>{{cite web|last1=Guy|first1=Jim|url=http://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/crime/article145212769.html|title=Kori Ali Muhammad also suspected in Motel 6 slaying|newspaper=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> He was a friend of the daughter of the woman at the hotel.<ref name=fresnobee5/> On the same morning, Muhammad went to a [[Starbucks]] coffee shop while out to purchase items for use in voodoo rituals. He used the shop's [[Wi-Fi]] to watch a broadcast by Fresno [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] affiliate [[KFSN-TV]], which identified him as a suspect in the security guard's murder.<ref name=abcnews3>{{cite web|last1=Jacobo|first1=Julia|last2=Stone|first2=Alex|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/fresno-police-chief-releases-details-hate-crime-shooting/story?id=46884877|title=Fresno police chief releases new details in 'hate crime' shooting rampage that killed 3|newspaper=[[ABC News]]|date=April 19, 2017|accessdate=April 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Downtown shootings===\nAfter being identified as a suspect in William's murder, Muhammad decided that he would not \"go down for one murder\" and that he \"might as well take out as many white men\" as he could.<ref name=yourcentralvalley:5/> Hours after the identification, several shootings were reported in downtown Fresno. Muhammad, first approached a [[Pacific Gas and Electric Company]] (PG&E) utility truck at about 10:45&nbsp;a.m. and fired four shots into it, critically wounding an employee seated in the passenger seat. The passenger of the vehicle was identified to be Zachary Randalls.<ref name=fresnobee>{{cite web|last1=Rodriguez|first1=Robert|url=https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/article240845736.html|title=Witness says alleged mass shooter Kori Muhammad had \u2018cold\u2019 look during killing|newspaper=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=March 3, 2020|accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref> The driver of that truck was spared from being shot, since he was deemed Hispanic and thus non white by Muhammad. The driver managed to drive away unharmed, and took Randalls to the [[Fresno Police Department]] headquarters, where he alerted officers. Randalls was taken to [[Community Regional Medical Center]], where he later died.<ref name=fresnobee6/><ref name=fresnobee3>{{cite web|last1=Guy|first1=Jim|url=http://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/crime/article145234709.html|title=Three dead in Fresno shooting rampage; suspected gunman linked to killing of motel guard|newspaper=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref><ref name=kabc1>{{cite web|url=http://abc7.com/news/fresno-triple-shooting-leaves-2-dead;-gunman-at-large/1888575/|title=Fresno Triple Shooting a Hate Crime, Not Act of Terrorism, Police Say|newspaper=[[KABC-TV]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref><ref name=abcnews1>{{cite web|last1=Smith|first1=Scott|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/killed-hurt-shooting-downtown-fresno-california-46870435|title=Fresno shooter wanted to kill many white people, police say|newspaper=[[ABC News]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Pope|first1=Troy|url=http://www.yourcentralvalley.com/news/fresno-police-seek-man-with-shooting-spree-murder-weapon/694537449|title=Fresno police seek man with shooting spree murder weapon|newspaper=Your Central Valley|date=April 19, 2017|accessdate=April 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn Muhammad's murder trial, the driver of the utility truck testified that the truck was in park when Muhammad approached them sitting in it. From Muhammad's facial expression, the driver said Muhammad had a \"cold, dark look\" which was unnerving. The driver nodded to Muhammad as a gesture from his window, to which Muhammad was unresponsive. Muhammad walked past the drivers left fender and then stopped,  looking into the truck again. The driver told Randalls that he was suspicious of Muhammad's behavior at this moment. As Muhammad reached into his jacket the driver immediately put the truck in reverse. Muhammad fired his gun a few times at the passengers side at Randalls as the driver was backing up. As he backed up a sufficient distance from Muhammad, Muhammad fired off one last shot which hit the head rest of Randall's seat. Randalls told the driver that he was shot. The driver called [[9-1-1]] emergency and drove to the police station because he didn't know where the closest hospital was.<ref name=\"fresnobee\">{{cite web|last1=Rodriguez|first1=Robert|url=https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/article240845736.html|title=Witness says alleged mass shooter Kori Muhammad had \u2018cold\u2019 look during killing|newspaper=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=March 3, 2020|accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref> The driver stated that Randalls lost consciousness on the way to the police station.<ref name=yourcentralvalley2>{{cite web|last1=Lei Lani|first1=Angelica|url=https://www.yourcentralvalley.com/news/accused-spree-killer-kori-muhammad-leaves-during-court-as-witnesses-and-victims-testified-in-his-trial/|title=Accused spree-killer Kori Muhammad leaves during court as witnesses and victims testify in his trial|newspaper=yourcentralvalley , [[KGPE]]|date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=March 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSeconds after shooting four rounds into the PG&E truck on N. Van Ness, Muhammad proceeded south to Mildreda turning west. Kori Muhammad fired two more shots at a 59-year-old man coming out of his house, but missed. The second shot hit a residential dwelling on the other side of the street.<ref name=fresnobee6/> Then Muhammad reloaded his revolver in the alley between Van Ness and Fulton. Muhammad stated he thought about pursuing the 59-year-old man believing he had gone back inside his house but changed his mind. Muhammad then turned onto N Fulton St heading south, where he fired once at a vehicle containing a woman, her adult daughter, and her four-year-old granddaughter, but stopped shooting after realizing they were [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Latino]]. No one in the vehicle suffered any gunshot wounds.<ref name=fresnobee6/><ref name=abcnews3/><ref name=cnn2/><ref name=portlandpress>{{cite web|last1=Smith|first1=Scott|url=http://www.pressherald.com/2017/04/18/police-say-man-who-shot-and-killed-three-shouted-god-is-great-in-arabic/|title=Triple killer in Fresno motivated by hate, not terrorism, police say|newspaper=[[Portland Press Herald]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nMuhammad then walked down the opposite direction, where he spotted a man, Mark Gassett, walking out of a [[Catholic Charities USA]] building. He shot Gassett once in the chest, then killed him with two more shots after he had fallen to the ground.<ref name=\"fresnobee:1\">{{cite web|last1=George|first1=Carmen|last2=Benjamin|first2=Marc|url=https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/crime/article145569374.html|title=\u2018The racism needs to stop,\u2019 says family of shooting victim Mark Gassett, killed walking home with groceries|newspaper=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=April 19, 2017|accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"abc30:3\">{{cite web|last1=Hoggard|first1=Corin|url=https://abc30.com/1888358/|title=Gunman targeting white men kills 3, Fresno Police Chief says; 1 victim identified|newspaper=[[KFSN-TV]], ABC30|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Muhammad then reloaded at a bus stop and fired at three white men. Two of them escaped unharmed, but Muhammad chased the third man, David Jackson.<ref name=\"CNN:2\">{{cite web|last1=Yan|first1=Holly|url=https://www.cnn.com/2017/04/19/us/fresno-shooting-rampage-timeline/index.html|title=Fresno rampage suspect details each day of killing spree to police|newspaper=[[CNN]]|date=April 19, 2017|accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref> Jackson, who was the heaviest and oldest, was followed into the parking lot of a [[Catholic Charities USA]] building. There Muhammad fired six shots: two that killed the Jackson, two that struck parked vehicles, one that struck a nearby building, and a sixth that has yet to be recovered. Witnesses said that Muhammad cursed as he fired.<ref name=fresnobee6/><ref name=abcnews3/><ref name=fresnobee3/><ref name=time1>{{cite web|last1=Smith|first1=Scott|last2=Bollag|first2=Sophia|url=http://time.com/4747423/fresno-shooting-kori-ali-muhammad/|title=Fresno Shooting Suspect Laughed About the Killings in Police Interviews|newspaper=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=April 19, 2017|accessdate=April 19, 2017}}</ref><ref name=cnn2>{{cite web|last1=Hanna|first1=Jason|last2=Mossburg|first2=Cheri|last3=Simon|first3=Darran|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/04/19/us/fresno-shootings-hate-crime/|title=Fresno shooting: Rampage started with slaying last week, police say|newspaper=[[CNN]]|date=April 19, 2017|accessdate=April 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOfficers responding to [[shotspotter]] reports found Muhammad running down the street, and managed to arrest him.<ref name=fresnobee3/> During the arrest, Muhammad shouted, \"''[[Takbir|Allahu Akbar]]''!\"<ref name=newsweek1/> Several bullets and [[speedloader]]s for a [[.357 Magnum]] revolver were recovered from his person, but no firearm was found.<ref name=fresnobee3/> According to Chief Jerry Dyer, the gun was wrapped in clothing and picked up by a [[Hispanic]] male who had met up with Muhammad shortly after the shootings and then fled the scene.<ref name=fresnobee6/><ref name=abcnews3/> Dyer also said a total of seventeen shots were fired in 90 seconds during these shootings.<ref name=abcnews3/><ref name=bbc1>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-39636104|title=California gunman kills three 'in race attack' in Fresno|newspaper=[[BBC News]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref><ref name=latimes1>{{cite web|last1=Rocha|first1=Veronica|last2=Serna|first2=Joseph|last3=Marcum|first3=Diana|last4=Branson-Potts|first4=Hailey|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-fresno-shooting-20170418-story.html|title=Hate crime is suspected after a gunman kills 3 white men in downtown Fresno|newspaper=[[The Los Angeles Times]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> Four minutes had passed between the first shots and Muhammad's arrest.<ref name=fresnobee6/> Several streets and county government buildings were put on [[lockdown]] during the shootings, with people being ordered to [[shelter in place]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.turnto23.com/news/state/2-dead-1-injured-in-fresno-shooting|title=3 dead in 3 different locations in Fresno shooting|newspaper=[[KERO-TV]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Whitcomb|first1=Dan|last2=Gorman|first2=Steve|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-california-shooting-idUSKBN17K2DJ|title=Gunman targeting white men kills 3 in Fresno, California|newspaper=[[Reuters]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] and [[Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives|ATF]] were notified of the shootings.<ref name=fresnobee3/> Agents from the [[United States Department of Homeland Security|Department of Homeland Security]] also responded to the Fresno Police Department headquarters.<ref name=newsweek1>{{cite web|last1=Le Miere|first1=Jason|url=http://www.newsweek.com/kori-ali-muhammad-fresno-shootiung-585806|title=In Fresno Shooting, Suspect Kori Ali Muhammad Shouted 'Allahu Akbar,' Wrote About Hatred of White People|newspaper=[[Newsweek]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> Chief Dyer said that the incident was \"a random act of violence\" and that the gunman acted alone, adding that it was \"too soon\" to determine whether the shootings were acts of terrorism.<ref name=fresnobee3/> A federal law enforcement official said the shootings did not bear the hallmarks of a terrorist attack and appeared to be more of a \"local, criminal matter\".<ref name=washingtonpost1>{{cite web|last1=Berman|first1=Mark|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-nation/wp/2017/04/18/3-people-killed-during-unprovoked-shooting-rampage-in-fresno-police-say/|title=Three people killed in \u2018unprovoked\u2019 Fresno shooting rampage \u2018motivated by hate,\u2019 police say|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nLocal authorities said they would investigate the shootings as a [[hate crime]].<ref name=latimes1/> Chief Dyer said that Kori Muhammad, who is [[Black people|black]], told police he decided to become infamous for killing many white people after realizing he was wanted in the Motel 6 shooting.<ref name=portlandpress/><ref name=wboc>{{cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/35180183/the-latest-police-say-fresno-man-shot-3-after-being-ided|title=The Latest: Brother of Fresno suspect shocked by killings|newspaper=[[WBOC-TV]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419193128/http://www.wboc.com/story/35180183/the-latest-police-say-fresno-man-shot-3-after-being-ided|archive-date=April 19, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=mercurynews>{{cite web|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/2017/04/18/the-latest-3-shot-killed-in-california-suspect-caught/|title=The Latest: Brother of Fresno suspect shocked by killings|newspaper=[[The Mercury News]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> Muhammad led investigators through the murder scenes and described exactly how he committed the shooting rampage, laughing all the while.<ref name=abcnews3/><ref name=yourcentralvalley3>{{cite web|last1=Lei Lani|first1=Angelica|url=https://www.yourcentralvalley.com/news/crime/smiling-laughing-and-a-fist-bump-muhammad-trial-includes-autopsies-and-interview-video-2/|title=Smiling, laughing, and a fist-bump: Muhammad trial includes autopsies and interview video|newspaper=yourcentralvalley , [[KGPE]]|date=March 10, 2020|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAll of the victims killed in the shootings were white males.<ref name=washingtonpost1/> The Motel 6 security guard was identified as 25-year-old Carl Williams.<ref name=fresnobee2/> The victims of the April 18 shootings were identified the next day as PG&E employee Zackary David Randalls, 34, of [[Clovis, California|Clovis]]; and Mark James Gassett, 37, and David Martin Jackson, 58, both of Fresno.<ref name=abcnews3/><ref name=nbcnews2>{{cite web|last1=Johnson|first1=Alex|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/fresno-gunman-targeted-many-white-males-possible-cops-say-n748566|title=Fresno Gunman Targeted \u2018as Many White Males as Possible,\u2019 Cops Say|newspaper=[[NBC News]]|date=April 19, 2017|accessdate=April 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nMayor [[Lee Brand]] offered his condolences to the victims' families and called April 18 \"a sad day for us all\".<ref name=washingtonpost1/> PG&E expressed its own condolences to all those involved, including the family of the slain employee.<ref name=latimes1/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Pope|first1=Troy|url=http://www.yourcentralvalley.com/news/suspect-in-fresno-shooting-spree-that-killed-3-shouts-allahu-akbar-when-arrested/693838151|title=Suspect in Fresno shooting spree that killed 3 shouts 'Allahu Akbar' when arrested|newspaper=Your Central Valley|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Perpetrator==\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Kori Ali Muhammad\n| image = \n| image_upright = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| alias = Kori McDonald<ref name=abcnews3/><br>Kori MacSon McWallace<ref name=fresnobee4/><br>B-God MacSun\n| birth_name = Cory Allen Taylor\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1978|3|21}}<ref name=cbi>{{cite web|url=http://www.californiabirthindex.org/birth/cory_allen_taylor_born_1978_13842834 |title=Cory Allen Taylor |publisher=California Birth Index |accessdate=April 19, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419193351/http://www.californiabirthindex.org/birth/cory_allen_taylor_born_1978_13842834 |archivedate=April 19, 2017 }}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Fresno County]], California \n| residence = \n| education = [[American River College]]<br>[[Cosumnes River College]]<br>[[Fresno City College]]<br>[[Sacramento City College]]\n| nationality = American\n| children = 3\n}}\nKori Ali Muhammad (born March 21, 1978) was identified as the prime suspect in all of the shootings. He was homeless at the time,<ref name=fresnobee2/> and had some association with gangs, but wasn't a member of one himself.<ref name=washingtonpost1/> He has three children.<ref name=guardian/>\n\n===Personal background===\nBorn as '''Cory Allen Taylor''',<ref name=cbi/> and also previously known as '''Kori Taylor''',<ref name=heavy>{{cite web|last1=McBride|first1=Jessica|url=http://heavy.com/news/2017/04/kori-ali-muhammad-fresno-shooting-isis-allahu-akbar-terror-attack-photos-facebook-suspect-california/|title=Kori Ali Muhammad: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know|newspaper=[[Heavy.com]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> Muhammad changed his name to his present one as a teenager.<ref name=latimes2>{{cite web|last1=Serna|first1=Joseph|last2=Branson-Potts|first2=Hailey|last3=Queally|first3=James|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-fresno-shooter-suspect-20170418-story.html|title=Suspect in Fresno shooting rampage spoke about racial conflict and black nationalism|newspaper=[[The Los Angeles Times]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> His grandmother said that Muhammad had been drawn to [[Islam]] at a young age. Muhammad's aunt said that her nephew also attended a [[Baptists|Baptist]] church when he was younger.<ref name=guardian>{{cite web|last1=Levin|first1=Sam|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/apr/19/fresno-shooting-hate-crime-kori-ali-muhammad|title=Fresno shooting decried as anti-white hate crime, but truth is complicated|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=April 19, 2017|accessdate=April 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nMuhammad was a resident of both Fresno and [[Sacramento, California]]. According to Muhammad's [[Facebook]] page, he studied [[multimedia]] at [[Cosumnes River College]] in Sacramento. A spokesman for the [[Los Rios Community College District]] identified a student named Kori McWallace\u2014with the same date of birth as Muhammad\u2014who attended Cosumnes, [[American River College]], and [[Sacramento City College]] at various times from 1996 to 2004. However, no details were immediately offered about his studies or if he graduated.<ref name=sacbee1>{{cite web|last1=Stanton|first1=Sam|last2=Lambert|first2=Diana|url=http://www.sacbee.com/news/local/crime/article145324594.html|title=Suspect in Fresno slayings had ties to Sacramento, including a felony rap sheet|newspaper=[[The Sacramento Bee]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> Muhammad also attended classes at [[Fresno City College]], but according to a classmate, he would often not show up for weeks at a time and accuse his instructors of being racist.<ref name=bbc1/>\n\n===Previous criminal history===\nMuhammad had a criminal history dated from 1997 to 2004, consisting of arrests on weapons, drugs, forgery, and false imprisonment charges, as well as making terrorist threats.<ref name=abcnews1/><ref name=mercurynews/> Court documents also indicated that he \"suffered auditory hallucinations and had at least two prior mental health hospitalizations.\"<ref name=wboc/> Two of his earliest arrests occurred when he was still a teenager; on both occasions, he allegedly brought a gun to school. In 2004, Muhammad was arrested in [[Washington (state)|Washington state]] for allegedly firing a gun outside his apartment. He left the state and the case was dismissed after prosecutors declined to extradite him to a federal prison.<ref name=cbsnews3>{{cite web|url=http://cbsnews.com/amp/news/fresno-shooting-spree-suspect-had-criminal-history-said-he-joined-gang-at-9/|title=Fresno shooting spree suspect had criminal history, said he joined gang at 9|newspaper=[[CBS News]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=April 20, 2017|accessdate=April 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAccording to court records filed in February 2005, he was arrested and indicted in federal court on charges of \"possession of cocaine with intent to distribute, possession of a firearm for drug trafficking and possession of a firearm by a convicted felon\".<ref name=latimes1/> In September, Muhammad sought an insanity defense and underwent a psychiatric evaluation after his lawyer claimed his client was \"suffering from hallucinations, paranoia and psychosis.\"<ref name=sacbee1/><ref name=latimes3>{{cite web|url=http://documents.latimes.com/judge-commits-accused-fresno-shooter-facility-because-he-was-mental-health-issues/|title=Criminal history of accused Fresno shooter Kori Ali Muhammad: Committed to mental health facility|newspaper=[[The Los Angeles Times]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> A judge ruled that he was incompetent to stand trial and had him committed to a facility for up to four months.<ref name=latimes3/> He was deemed competent in August 2006, after which he pleaded guilty to two of seven counts in the indictment. Muhammad was sentenced to over nine years in prison, though the sentence was downgraded to over seven years in 2008. He was released from prison early in September 2016.<ref name=latimes1/><ref name=heavy/><ref name=sacbee1/>\n\nMuhammad claimed to have shot a person at the age of twelve, but the claim was not confirmed by police.<ref name=fresnobee6/>\n\n===Views and statements===\nMuhammad maintained two Facebook profiles and a [[Twitter]] account,<ref name=fresnobee4>{{cite web|last1=Appleton|first1=Rory|url=http://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/crime/article145293959.html|title=Suspected Fresno rampage killer may have threatened Trump on social media|newspaper=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> all in which he paid homage to [[black pride]] and [[black nationalism]]. His profile depicted images of a [[Black Power]] [[Raised fist|salute]] and [[Pan-African flag|a flag]] associated with the [[Pan-Africanism]] movement.<ref name=latimes2/> According to police, he \"expressed hatred of whites\" and the government.<ref name=fresnobee3/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2017/04/18/fresno-shooting-spree-3-people-killed-suspect-in-custody.html|title=Fresno shooting rampage: Suspect who shot dead 3 wanted to kill as many people as possible, police say|newspaper=[[FOX News]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> Muhammad made posts about [[2016 shooting of Dallas police officers|the murders of five Dallas police officers]], in which he praised the shooter Micah Xavier Johnson.<ref name=heavy/> He also consistently used the [[hashtag]] \"#LetBlackPeopleGo\" and encouraged \"black warriors\" to \"mount up\".<ref name=time1/> Muhammad's father described his son's belief that there was an ongoing war between whites and blacks, and that \"a battle was about to take place.\"<ref name=latimes1/> He later said that he attempted to warn Muhammad's probation officer about his son's hatred of white people and his plans of killing them, but believes no one followed up on his report.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hoggard|first1=Corin|url=http://abc30.com/news/father-of-fresno-shooting-spree-suspect-talks-about-son/1893733/|title=Father of Fresno Shooting Spree Suspect Talks About Son|newspaper=[[KFSN-TV]]|date=April 19, 2017|accessdate=April 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn a phone interview with an ABC News affiliate in downtown Fresno Jail, Kori Ali Muhammad spoke about his motives for the killings. Muhammad spoke about his hatred for [[white people]] and especially white men. Muhammad stated that \"someone has to fight for them. Someone has to fight for all the people that died at the hands of racist white men.\" \nMuhammad was initially wanted by [[Fresno]] police for the death of Carl Williams, a security guard he killed a few days before his shooting spree. Muhammad added that \"I was actually going to turn myself in.Then I started thinking about the missing black women and children... started thinking about Flint Michigan...starting thinking about the crack cocaine epidemic...started thinking about all the injustices and atrocities that my people go through. That's why I snapped. I wasn't thinking like I'm going to kill, kill, kill, all I know was that white supremacy has to die and people that benefit most from white supremacy are white men.\"\nMuhammad believed himself to be a martyr saying \"I gave my life for the freedom of people. The ultimate freedom of my people.\"<ref name=KCRA2>{{cite web|url=https://www.kcra.com/article/fresno-shootings-woman-wont-be-charged-in-guards-death/9660774|title=Fresno shootings: Woman won't be charged in guard's death|newspaper=[[KCRA-TV]]|date=May 16, 2017|accessdate=February 11, 2020}}</ref>\nMuhammad stated that \u201cConsidering the crime I did, I can live with having to be in jail, like I know what I did was wrong.\u201d When asked if he regretted killing four people Muhammad stated that he did not.<ref name=yourcentralvalley>{{cite web|last1=Lei Lani|first1=Angelica|url=https://www.yourcentralvalley.com/news/crime/would-you-rather-i-be-dead-muhammad-trial-hears-calls-he-made-to-his-mother-after-his-arrest/|title=\u2018Would you rather I be dead?\u2019; Muhammad trial hears calls he made to his mother after his arrest|newspaper=yourcentralvalley , [[KGPE]]|date=March 11, 2020|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn Muhammad's [[capital punishment]] trial, Muhammad chose to testify and answer questions about his killing spree. When asked if he intended to kill a white man, Zachary Randalls in the [[PG&E]] truck, Muhammad stated that \"I wanted to kill them, yes\". Muhammad kept alluding to his own version of ancient [[religious]] prophesies. Muhammad stated that \u201cGod is going to destroy white men in particular, specifically. It was written and 25,000 years ago that this had to happen.\u201d Muhammad also compared his killings to the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|coronavirus]], stating that he shot Mark Gassett when he was on the ground to make sure he was dead. Muhammad stated \"I wanted to kill him, just like the coronavirus is killing white men right now.\"<ref name=yourcentralvalley4>{{cite web|last1=Lei Lani|first1=Angelica|url=https://www.yourcentralvalley.com/news/i-wanted-to-kill-them-yes-kori-muhammad-takes-the-stand-in-murder-trial/|title=\u2018I wanted to kill them, yes\u2019: Kori Muhammad takes the stand in murder trial|newspaper=yourcentralvalley , [[KGPE]]|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring testimony, Muhammad claimed he was a god, and stated that God would destroy America if African-Americans were not given reparations. He also claimed to take credit for the destruction of [[Paradise, California]] during the 2018 [[Camp Fire (2018)]].<ref name=yourcentralvalley:5/>\n\n\n\nAccording to ''[[The Daily Beast]]'', Muhammad's posts indicated a support of the [[Moorish Science Temple of America]], an [[African Americans|African American]] organization associated with the [[sovereign citizen movement]], which advocated few beliefs similar to those of mainstream [[Islam]].<ref name=heavy/> Brian Levin, director of [[California State University, San Bernardino|Cal State San Bernardino]]'s Center for the Study of Hate and Extremism, said that Muhammad's social media posts made multiple references to terms used by the [[Nation of Islam]] (NOI),<ref name=latimes2/> a [[black supremacist]] organization labeled as a [[hate group]] by the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]] and the [[Anti-Defamation League]].<ref name=\"SPLC:1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.splcenter.org/fighting-hate/extremist-files/group/nation-islam|title=Nation of Islam|publisher=[[Southern Poverty Law Center]]|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ADL:1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/resources/profiles/the-nation-of-islam|title=The Nation of Islam|publisher=[[Anti-Defamation League]]|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref> Muhammad made references to \"grafted white devils\", an expression frequently used in the Nation of Islam to describe [[white people]], and \"Yakub\", the villainous figure responsible for creating white people in the Nation of Islam.<ref name=latimes2/><ref name=\"SPLC:2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.splcenter.org/hatewatch/2017/04/19/possible-black-separatist-kori-ali-muhammad-kills-three-fresno|title=Possible Black Separatist Kori Ali Muhammad Kills Three in Fresno|newspaper=[[Southern Poverty Law Center]]|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref> \nMuhammad said he drew inspiration from [[Wallace Fard Muhammad]], an important figure in the Nation of Islam.<ref name=\"fox23\">{{cite web|last1=Lehnert|first1=Alexandra|url=https://kmph.com/news/local/learning-more-about-kori-muhammad|title=Learning more about Kori Muhammad|newspaper=[[KMPH-TV]]|date=April 20, 2017|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref name=latimes1/> Muhammad's relatives said that he \"became involved\" with the NOI when he was younger, but did not clarify what kind of role the group played in his life during his imprisonment and after his release.<ref name=guardian/>\n\nMuhammad's beliefs included a mixture of the Nation of Islam and also [[voodoo]] which he said is called Kali Sufi. He used amulets and necklaces for his voodoo religion, and referred to himself as a god.<ref name=\"abc30:I am a god\">{{cite web|last1=Hoggard|first1=Corin|url=https://abc30.com/kori-muhammad-admits-to-killing-4-people/6022284/|title='I am a god': Fresno mass shooting suspect Kori Muhammad admits to killing 4 people|newspaper=[[KFSN-TV]], ABC30|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February, Muhammad released two [[hip-hop]] albums on [[iTunes]] and [[YouTube]] under the name of '''B-God MacSun'''. ''[[The Los Angeles Times]]'' noted that Muhammad sang that he was an \"[[Asia]]tic black god\", and that the album's contents \"repeatedly references violence between black and white people.\"<ref name=latimes1/><ref name=fresnobee4/><ref name=latimes2/>\n\nIn addition, Muhammad produced a music-themed talk show at the Community Media Access Collaborative, a [[nonprofit organization]] specializing in promoting people and companies through the use of media. Muhammad's talk show ran for four episodes, which were produced between May 12, 2015, and October 10, 2016.<ref name=fresnobee4/> In that talk show, he claimed that he had joined a Sacramento gang at the age of nine, the \"black liberation movement\" at the age of fourteen, and the NOI later on in his teens.<ref name=cbsnews3/> The organization's director of operations described Muhammad, a frequenter at the facility, as \"kind and curious\" to the staff.<ref name=fresnobee4/> However, a former friend who met Muhammad at the facility, but later removed him from his [[Friending and following|friended]] list on Facebook, described him as \"intense and unnerving\"<ref name=nbcnews2/>\n\nAn [[imam]] at a local mosque said that Muhammad was not a member of his congregation.<ref name=washingtonpost1/> Following his arrest, Muhammad affirmed to officers that he is Muslim, but that he had not been to a mosque in 25 years and that he prays to a total of seven different deities.<ref name=time1/> He also told officers that he was not officially affiliated with any terrorist groups.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mays|first1=Mackenzie|last2=Anderson|first2=Barbara|url=http://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/crime/article145629169.html|title=Experts say shooting rampage is a hate crime \u2013 but not an act of terrorism. Here\u2019s why.|newspaper=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=April 19, 2017|accessdate=April 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Legal proceedings==\nFollowing his arrest, Muhammad was charged with four counts of [[murder]] and two counts of assault with a deadly weapon.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mossburg|first1=Cheri|last2=Simon|first2=Darran|last3=Park|first3=Madison|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/04/18/us/fresno-california-shootings/|title=Police chief: Fresno killings a hate crime|newspaper=[[CNN]]|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> On April 21, he made his first court appearance for the first-degree murder of Carl Williams and the attempted murder of the second security guard at the Motel 6. During the hearing, he shouted on two different occasions, saying \"Let black people go\" and a phrase similar to \"in reparations\" that was not clearly enunciated. He also warned that natural disasters striking the U.S. will increase. As a result, criminal proceedings were suspended and the judge ordered a psychiatric evaluation for Muhammad, setting bail at $2.6 million. Muhammad faces the death penalty if convicted of all four murders.<ref name=latimes4/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Lopez|first1=Pablo|url=http://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/crime/article145958869.html|title=Fresno shooting spree: \u2018Let black people go!\u2019 Kori Muhammad yells in court|newspaper=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=April 21, 2017|accessdate=April 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/latest-fresno-california-gunman-enters-court-shouting-46938448|title=Fresno, California gunman enters court shouting|newspaper=[[ABC News]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=April 21, 2017|accessdate=April 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/newswires/news/national/fresno-killing-suspect-shouts-1st-court-hearing-article-1.3083872|title=Fresno killing suspect shouts out during 1st court hearing|newspaper=[[The New York Daily News]]|date=April 21, 2017|accessdate=April 21, 2017}}</ref> His next court appearance was scheduled on May 12,<ref name=latimes4/> but postponed to June 1 to give psychologists more time to prepare Muhammad's mental health report.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Appleton|first1=Rory|title=Psychologist needs more time to evaluate Fresno shooting suspect\u2019s mental state, judge says|url=http://www.modbee.com/article150158612.html|newspaper=[[The Modesto Bee]]|date=May 12, 2017|accessdate=May 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn October 13, 2017 the judge set a trial date for January 8, 2018. The initial hearings will focus on Muhammad's mental competency. During the hearings Muhammad shouted demands for slavery reparations and also yelled \"Allahu akbar.\" Muhammad's lawyer says he continues to gather evidence that he is incompetent to be held criminally responsible. Two psychiatrists have determined that he is incompetent but another says that he is not.<ref name=\"FresnoTV\">{{cite news|last1=Haagenson|first1=Gene|title=Mental competency trial date set for Fresno shooting spree suspect|url=http://abc30.com/mental-competency-trial-date-set-for-fresno-shooting-spree-suspect/2529165/|accessdate=27 November 2017|publisher=ABC 30 Action News|date=13 October 2017}}</ref> Dr. Meloy declared Muhammad competent and stated that \"He knows the \"shrink talk\". He knows how to communicate to a psychologist or psychiatrist when he's being interviewed because he knows what the psychiatrist or psychologist is looking for.\" Dr Meloy believed that Muhammad's schizophrenia was managed effectively and that it was a non factor in Muhammad's thinking to deduce right from wrong in the killings.<ref name=\"abc30:2\">{{cite web|last1=Rose|first1=Sontaya|url=https://abc30.com/kori-muhammad-an-expert-at-pretending-to-be-delusional-for-his-benefit-da-says/2965961/|title=Kori Muhammad an expert at pretending to be delusional for his benefit, DA says|newspaper=[[KFSN-TV]], ABC30|date=January 19, 2018|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> On January 22, 2018, Judge Jonathan Conklin ruled that Muhammad is competent to stand trial.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lopez|first1=Pablo|url=http://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/crime/article195944044.html|title=Accused Fresno rampage killer is competent to stand trial, judge rules|newspaper=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=January 22, 2018|accessdate=January 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fresnobee.com/news/state/california/article196030899.html|title=California judge: Alleged killer of 4 mentally fit for trial|newspaper=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=January 22, 2018|accessdate=January 23, 2018|website=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180124005809/http://www.fresnobee.com/news/state/california/article196030899.html|archive-date=January 24, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nJury selection for Muhammad's trial began on February 4, 2020<ref name=yourcentralvalley1>{{cite web|last1=Lei Lani|first1=Angelica|url=https://www.yourcentralvalley.com/news/mother-of-shooting-victim-speaks-as-jury-selection-for-alleged-killers-trial-begins/|title=Mother of shooting victim speaks as jury selection for alleged killer\u2019s trial begins|newspaper=[[KGPE]]|date=February 4, 2020|accessdate=February 11, 2020}}</ref> and the trial began on March 2.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/crime/article240813601.html|title=Opening statements heard as the murder trial for Kori Ali Muhammad begins|date=March 2, 2020|website=fresnobee.com}}</ref>  \nMuhammad faces four murder charges and four attempted murder charges. Fresno District Attorney Lisa A. Smittcamp is seeking the [[death penalty]].<ref name=yourcentralvalley1/>\n\nMuhammad testified in court that he shot and killed Carl Williams. He testified that he later went on a shooting spree and shot and killed Zachary Randalls, Mark Gassett, and David Jackson, and shot at three other white men. Muhammad confessed to trying to kill as many white men as he could. When asked why he shot Mark Gassett while he lay on the ground wounded from the previous shots, Muhammad admitted that his intention was \"to kill him, just like the coronavirus is killing white men.\" He made several more references to the [[coronavirus]] when confessing to shooting people at the bus stop.<ref name=yourcentralvalley:5>{{cite web|last1=Pope |first1=Troy|url=https://www.yourcentralvalley.com/news/crime/muhammad-takes-the-stand-in-murder-trial-confesses-to-killing-4-men/|title=Muhammad takes the stand in murder trial, confesses to killing 4 men|newspaper=yourcentralvalley [[KGPE]]|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[2016 shooting of Baton Rouge police officers]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC8WX2lUGdDv9UeVaq6CFvig Kori Ali Muhammad's YouTube channel]\n*[https://www.yourcentralvalley.com/news/crime/muhammad-takes-the-stand-in-murder-trial-confesses-to-killing-4-men/ Kori Ali Muhammad's confession in murder trial]\n*[https://www.docketalarm.com/cases/California_State_Fresno_County_Superior_Court/F17902482/The_People_of_the_State_of_California_vs._Kori_Ali_Muhammad/ The People of the State of California vs. Kori Ali Muhammad]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fresno shooting spree, 2017}}\n[[Category:Spree shootings in the United States]]\n[[Category:2017 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:April 2017 crimes in the United States]]\n[[Category:2017 crimes in California]]\n[[Category:2010s in Fresno, California|2017 shootings]]\n[[Category:Racially motivated violence against European Americans]]\n", "name_user": "Hernando12375", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDowntown shootings", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2017_Fresno_shooting_spree"}
{"title_page": "Frederic Cliffe", "text_new": "'''Frederic Cliffe''' (2 May 1857 \u2013 19 November 1931) was an English [[composer]].\n\n==Life==\nCliffe was born in [[Bradford]], [[Yorkshire]].  As a youth, he showed a promising musical aptitude and was enrolled as a scholar of the National Training School for Music, the parent of the [[Royal College of Music]], under its first Principal  [[Arthur Sullivan]].<ref name=\"RCM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cph.rcm.ac.uk/Tour/Pages/Cliffe.htm|title=Frederic Cliffe (1857-1931)|publisher=Royal College of Music|year=2004|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418173253/http://www.cph.rcm.ac.uk/Tour/Pages/Cliffe.htm|archivedate=2015-04-18|accessdate=2015-12-01}}</ref> As well as Sullivan his teachers there included [[John Stainer]], [[Ebenezer Prout]] and Franklin Taylor (1843-1919). In 1873 at the age of sixteen he was appointed organist to the [[Bradford Festival Choral Society]].<ref>Leach, Gerald. ''British Composer Profiles'', 3rd Edition (2012)</ref> As organist to the [[Leeds Festival (classical music)|Leeds Festival]], Cliffe took part in the first performance of Sullivan's cantata [[The Golden Legend (cantata)|''The Golden Legend'']] on 6 October 1886.<ref name=MT>''Musical Times'' obituary, January 1932, p 80</ref>\n\nFrom 1884 to 1931 he held the post of Professor of Piano at the Royal College of Music.<ref name=\"RCM\"/>  Among his pupils there were [[John Ireland (composer)|John Ireland]] and [[Arthur Benjamin]]. Cliffe was also occasionally connected with opera productions at [[Theatre Royal, Drury Lane]], [[Her Majesty's Theatre]] and [[Royal Opera House|Covent Garden]].<ref name=MT/>\n\nCliffe had a short career as a composer from 1889 to 1905. His principal works were his two symphonies, the first of which was produced  by [[August Manns]] at [[The Crystal Palace]] in 1889, and subsequently performed at a Philharmonic concert, being well received on each occasion, with ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' hailing it as \"a masterpiece\". Although not overtly programmatic, its first movement was influenced by a visit to [[Norway]] by Cliffe. It was published by Novello.  His Second Symphony had its first performance at the [[Leeds Festival (classical music)|Leeds Festival]] in 1892. Cliffe gave titles to each of its movements: I. At Sunset. II. Night. III. Fairy Revels. IV. Morning.  It has been edited (2010) by Lionel Harrison and published by Patrick Meadows.\n\nHis 'scena', ''The Triumph of Alcestis'', for contralto voice and orchestra, was composed for [[Clara Butt]], and from 1905 his setting of [[Shelley]]'s ''[[Ode to the West Wind]]'' was popular with choral societies. However, after that seventeen-year period of producing substantial works he stopped composing altogether, and subsequently his works received few performances during his lifetime. For a time Cliffe was a professor at the [[Royal Academy of Music]], though he maintained his links to the end of his life Royal College as a senior member of the Board of Professors. He also travelled widely as an examiner to the [[Associated Board|Associated Board of Music]].<ref name=MT/>\n\nCliffe died in [[London]], aged 74. His son Cedric Cliffe wrote the librettos for operas by [[Arthur Benjamin]] and [[Joan Trimble]]<ref>[https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/page/8fba50823e2e4413b76ff784e78a624a ''Radio Times'' Issue 1749, 19 May 1957, p 6, 17]</ref>\n\n==Works==\n*''Symphony in C minor '', 1889 (pub. 2019 Scores Reformed)<ref>[https://scoresreformed.co.uk/store-2/Frederic-Cliffe-Symphony-in-C-minor-p144397578 Scores Reformed Ltd]</ref>\n*''Orchestral Picture: Cloud and Sunshine'', Philharmonic Society 1890\n*''Symphony in E minor'', 1892 (pub. 2010 Soundpost)\n*''[[Violin Concerto (Cliffe)|Violin Concerto in D minor]]'', 1896 (pub. 2007 Soundpost)\n*''The Triumph of Alcestis'', Scena for Contralto and Orchestra, Sheffield Festival 1902\n*''Ode to the North-East Wind'', Choral Ballad, Norwich Festival 1905\n*\"A Silent Voice\", song\n*''Coronation March'' 1910\n\n==Recordings==\nThe Symphony No. 1 in C minor and his tone poem 'Cloud and Sunshine' have been recorded (Sterling CDS-1055-2 (2003)) by the Malm\u00f6 Opera Orchestra conducted by Christopher Fifield.<ref>{{harvnb|Barnett|2003}}</ref>\n\nHis Violin Concerto in D minor was edited in 2007 by Christopher Fifield and published by Patrick Meadows, and has now been recorded by Philippe Graffin on [[Hyperion Records|Hyperion]] (CDA67838) with the BBC National Orchestra of Wales conducted by David Lloyd-Jones.<ref>{{harvnb|Schaarw\u00e4chter|2003}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 [[musicologist]] Christopher Fifield led the Lambeth Orchestra in a performance of the Symphony No. 2 in E minor that was subsequencly released privately.<ref>{{harvnb|Barnett|2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{Reflist}}\n\n;Sources\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.musicweb-international.com/classrev/2003/Nov03/Cliffe_symphony1.htm|last=Barnett|first=Rob|title=Review - Cliffe:Symphony N\u00ba. 1/''Cloud and Sunshine''|publisher=Musicweb International|year=2003|ref={{harvid|Barnett|2003}}}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.musicweb-international.com/classrev/2015/Nov/Cliffe_sy2.htm|last=Barnett|first=Rob|title=Review - Cliffe:Symphony N\u00ba.2/Coronation March|publisher=Musicweb International|date=2015-11-30|accessdate=2015-11-30|ref={{harvid|Barnett|2015}}}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.musicweb-international.com/cliffe/index.htm|last=Schaarw\u00e4chter|first=Julian|title=Frederic Cliffe: British Symphonist|publisher=Musicweb International|year=2003|ref={{harvid|Schaarw\u00e4chter|2003}}}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cliffe, Frederic}}\n[[Category:1857 births]]\n[[Category:1931 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:Academics of the Royal College of Music]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal College of Music]]\n[[Category:English classical composers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:People from Bradford]]\n[[Category:English Romantic composers]]\n[[Category:English male classical composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century English musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century British composers]]\n[[Category:19th-century British composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male musicians]]\n[[Category:19th-century male musicians]]\n\n\n{{UK-composer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Frederic Cliffe''' (2 May 1857 \u2013 19 November 1931) was an English [[composer]].\n\n==Life==\nCliffe was born in [[Bradford]], [[Yorkshire]].  As a youth, he showed a promising musical aptitude and was enrolled as a scholar of the National Training School for Music, the parent of the [[Royal College of Music]], under its first Principal  [[Arthur Sullivan]].<ref name=\"RCM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cph.rcm.ac.uk/Tour/Pages/Cliffe.htm|title=Frederic Cliffe (1857-1931)|publisher=Royal College of Music|year=2004|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418173253/http://www.cph.rcm.ac.uk/Tour/Pages/Cliffe.htm|archivedate=2015-04-18|accessdate=2015-12-01}}</ref> As well as Sullivan his teachers there included [[John Stainer]], [[Ebenezer Prout]] and Franklin Taylor (1843-1919). In 1873 at the age of sixteen he was appointed organist to the [[Bradford Festival Choral Society]].<ref>Leach, Gerald. ''British Composer Profiles'', 3rd Edition (2012)</ref> As organist to the [[Leeds Festival (classical music)|Leeds Festival]], Cliffe took part in the first performance of Sullivan's cantata [[The Golden Legend (cantata)|''The Golden Legend'']] on 6 October 1886.<ref name=MT>''Musical Times'' obituary, January 1932, p 80</ref>\n\nFrom 1884 to 1931 he held the post of Professor of Piano at the Royal College of Music.<ref name=\"RCM\"/>  Among his pupils there were [[John Ireland (composer)|John Ireland]] and [[Arthur Benjamin]]. Cliffe was also occasionally connected with opera productions at [[Theatre Royal, Drury Lane]], [[Her Majesty's Theatre]] and [[Royal Opera House|Covent Garden]].<ref name=MT/>\n\nCliffe had a short career as a composer from 1889 to 1905. His principal works were his two symphonies, the first of which was produced  by [[August Manns]] at [[The Crystal Palace]] in 1889, and subsequently performed at a Philharmonic concert, being well received on each occasion, with ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' hailing it as \"a masterpiece\". Although not overtly programmatic, its first movement was influenced by a visit to [[Norway]] by Cliffe. It was published by Novello.  His Second Symphony had its first performance at the [[Leeds Festival (classical music)|Leeds Festival]] in 1892. Cliffe gave titles to each of its movements: I. At Sunset. II. Night. III. Fairy Revels. IV. Morning.  It has been edited (2010) by Lionel Harrison and published by Patrick Meadows.\n\nHis 'scena', ''The Triumph of Alcestis'', for contralto voice and orchestra, was composed for [[Clara Butt]], and from 1905 his setting of [[Shelley]]'s ''[[Ode to the West Wind]]'' was popular with choral societies. However, after that seventeen-year period of producing substantial works he stopped composing altogether, and subsequently his works received few performances during his lifetime. For a time Cliffe was a professor at the [[Royal Academy of Music]], though he maintained his links to the end of his life Royal College as a senior member of the Board of Professors. He also travelled widely as an examiner to the [[Associated Board|Associated Board of Music]].<ref name=MT/>\n\nCliffe died in [[London]], aged 74. His son Cedric Cliffe wrote the librettos for operas by [[Arthur Benjamin]] and [[Joan Trimble]]<ref>[https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/page/8fba50823e2e4413b76ff784e78a624a ''Radio Times'' Issue 1749, 19 May 1957, p 6, 17]</ref>\n\n==Works==\n*''Symphony in C minor '', 1889 (Scores Reformed Ltd, 2019)<ref>[https://scoresreformed.co.uk/store-2/Frederic-Cliffe-Symphony-in-C-minor-p144397578 Scores Reformed]</ref>\n*''Orchestral Picture: Cloud and Sunshine'', Philharmonic Society 1890\n*''Symphony in E minor'', 1892 (pub. 2010 Soundpost)\n*''[[Violin Concerto (Cliffe)|Violin Concerto in D minor]]'', 1896 (pub. 2007 Soundpost)\n*''The Triumph of Alcestis'', Scena for Contralto and Orchestra, Sheffield Festival 1902\n*''Ode to the North-East Wind'', Choral Ballad, Norwich Festival 1905\n*\"A Silent Voice\", song\n*''Coronation March'' 1910\n\n==Recordings==\nThe Symphony No. 1 in C minor and his tone poem 'Cloud and Sunshine' have been recorded (Sterling CDS-1055-2 (2003)) by the Malm\u00f6 Opera Orchestra conducted by Christopher Fifield.<ref>{{harvnb|Barnett|2003}}</ref>\n\nHis Violin Concerto in D minor was edited in 2007 by Christopher Fifield and published by Patrick Meadows, and has now been recorded by Philippe Graffin on [[Hyperion Records|Hyperion]] (CDA67838) with the BBC National Orchestra of Wales conducted by David Lloyd-Jones.<ref>{{harvnb|Schaarw\u00e4chter|2003}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 [[musicologist]] Christopher Fifield led the Lambeth Orchestra in a performance of the Symphony No. 2 in E minor that was subsequencly released privately.<ref>{{harvnb|Barnett|2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{Reflist}}\n\n;Sources\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.musicweb-international.com/classrev/2003/Nov03/Cliffe_symphony1.htm|last=Barnett|first=Rob|title=Review - Cliffe:Symphony N\u00ba. 1/''Cloud and Sunshine''|publisher=Musicweb International|year=2003|ref={{harvid|Barnett|2003}}}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.musicweb-international.com/classrev/2015/Nov/Cliffe_sy2.htm|last=Barnett|first=Rob|title=Review - Cliffe:Symphony N\u00ba.2/Coronation March|publisher=Musicweb International|date=2015-11-30|accessdate=2015-11-30|ref={{harvid|Barnett|2015}}}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.musicweb-international.com/cliffe/index.htm|last=Schaarw\u00e4chter|first=Julian|title=Frederic Cliffe: British Symphonist|publisher=Musicweb International|year=2003|ref={{harvid|Schaarw\u00e4chter|2003}}}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cliffe, Frederic}}\n[[Category:1857 births]]\n[[Category:1931 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:Academics of the Royal College of Music]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal College of Music]]\n[[Category:English classical composers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:People from Bradford]]\n[[Category:English Romantic composers]]\n[[Category:English male classical composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century English musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century British composers]]\n[[Category:19th-century British composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male musicians]]\n[[Category:19th-century male musicians]]\n\n\n{{UK-composer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Sfjohna", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWorks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frederic_Cliffe"}
{"title_page": "Marek Szmid", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Marek Szmid\n| image          =\n| caption        =\n| fullname       = Marek Andrezj Szmid<ref name=\"hugman\">{{Hugman|19166|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1982|3|2|df=y}}<ref name=\"hugman\"/>\n| birth_place    = [[Nuneaton]], England<ref name=\"hugman\"/>\n| height         = {{height|ft=5|in=8}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southendunited.co.uk/stats/view/player_profiles/0,,10444~22117,00.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020615003942/http://www.southendunited.co.uk/stats/view/player_profiles/0,,10444~22117,00.html |archivedate=15 June 2002 |title=Marek Szmid |work=SouthendUnited.co.uk |publisher=Southend United Football Club |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n| position       = [[Midfielder]]<ref name=\"hugman\"/>\n| youthyears1    = 1998\u20132001<ref name=\"redstat\">{{cite web|url=http://www.redstat.co.uk/?PlayerNo=301 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.vn/o6enu |archivedate=17 April 2020 |title=Marek Szmid |work=redStat.co.uk |publisher=redStat \u2212 Manchester United Statistics |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n| youthclubs1    = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]\n| years1         = 2001\u20132002\n| clubs1         = [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]]\n| caps1          = 2\n| goals1         = 0\n| years2         = 2002\u20132003\n| clubs2         = [[Sutton Coldfield Town F.C.|Sutton Coldfield Town]]\n| caps2          =\n| goals2         =\n| years3         = 2003\n| clubs3         = [[Marine F.C.|Marine]]\n| caps3          =\n| goals3         =\n| years4         = 2003\u20132004\n| clubs4         = [[Nuneaton Griff F.C.|Nuneaton Griff]]\n| caps4          =\n| goals4         =\n| years5         = 2004\u20132005\n| clubs5         = [[Nuneaton Town F.C.|Nuneaton Borough]]\n| caps5          =\n| goals5         =\n| years6         = 2004\u20132005\n| clubs6         = [[Liverpool John Moores University#Sports|Liverpool John Moores University]]\n| caps6          =\n| goals6         =\n| years7         = 2005\u20132006\n| clubs7         = [[Vauxhall Motors F.C.|Vauxhall Motors]]\n| caps7          =\n| goals7         =\n| totalcaps      =\n| totalgoals     =\n| nationalyears1 = 1997\u20131998\n| nationalteam1  = [[ESFA under-15 football team|ESFA U15]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 15\n| nationalgoals1 =\n| nationalyears2 = 1998\u20131999\n| nationalteam2  = [[England national under-16 football team|England U16]]\n| nationalcaps2  = 8\n| nationalgoals2 =\n| nationalyears3 =\n| nationalteam3  = [[England national under-17 football team|England U17]]\n| nationalcaps3  =\n| nationalgoals3 =\n| nationalyears4 = 2005\n| nationalteam4  = [[England national futsal team|England futsal]]\n| nationalcaps4  = 6\n| nationalgoals4 = 1\n}}\n'''Marek Andrezj Szmid''' (born 2 March 1982) is an English retired professional [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[midfielder]].\n\n==Early life==\nSzmid was born in [[Nuneaton]], Warkwickshire.<ref name=\"hugman\"/>\n\n==Club career==\n\nSzmid began his career with the youth team of [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] which he captained and then went on to make several reserve team appearances, before moving to [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]] in November 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/896023.stm|title=Football Transfers|date=1 August 2002|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southendunited.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10444~160586,00.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120531092310/http://www.southendunited.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10444~160586,00.html |archivedate=31 May 2012 |title=\"IT'S A GOOD CLUB\" - MAREK SZMID |work=SouthendUnited.co.uk |publisher=Southend United Football Club |date=17 November 2004 |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> He made 2 appearances in [[the Football League]] for Southend.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/southend/southend.html|title=SOUTHEND UNITED : 1946/47 \u2013 2009/10|publisher=Post War English & Scottish Football League A \u2013 Z Player's Database}}</ref><ref>{{soccerbase|29294}}</ref> Szmid later played non-league football with [[Sutton Coldfield Town F.C.|Sutton Coldfield Town]] and [[Marine F.C.|Marine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nonleaguedaily.com/news/index.php?newsmode=FULL&nid=14132 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121004022117/http://www.nonleaguedaily.com/news/index.php?newsmode=FULL&nid=14132 |archivedate=4 October 2012 |title=Latest Transfers |work=NonLeagueDaily.com |publisher=Baltic Publications Limited |date=29 November 2003 |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\nIn the same season he moved to play for [[Nuneaton Griff F.C.]].<ref>Coventry Evening Telegraph 10/09/2003</ref> In 2004, he played for [[Nuneaton Town F.C.]].<ref>Coventry Evening Telegraph 04/08/2004</ref> The next season saw him playing for [[Vauxhall Motors F.C.|Vauxhall Motors]].<ref>Liverpool Echo 06/08/2005</ref> That season saw him suffering a bad injury which caused him to retire from playing football. After retiring, he attended [[Liverpool John Moores University]] where he graduated with a B.A. in Sports Development in 2007.<ref>Liverpool John Moores University 2007 Graduates Award Ceremony</ref> Whilst studying he suffered a severe injury which caused his playing career to stop. The following year he attended the University of Chester where he took part in the GTP (Graduate Teacher Programme).<ref>University of Chester Graduates Award Ceremony 2008</ref> He started teaching Physical Education at Ashton-on-Mersey School in Trafford in 2008.<ref>http://issuu.com/ashton-on-mersey_school/docs/ashton_magazine_2011</ref> In September 2010 he started work as the Assistant Head of Education and Welfare at Manchester United F.C.<ref>http://youblisher.com/p/238592-Man-U-Tour-Diary-2011/</ref>\n\n==International career==\n===ESFA U15===\nSzmid represented [[ESFA Under-15|ESFA U-15]] and the team reached 3rd place of the mini World Cup at the Montaigu Tournament in France.<ref>ESFA Handbook 1998/99</ref> He was in the last ESFA Under-15 team, when they beat Germany 1\u20130 at the Olympic Stadium Berlin, before the Football Association took over the running of Schools Football. \n\n===England U16===\nSzmid represented [[England national under-16 football team|England]] at [[1999 UEFA European Under-16 Championship]] in the Czech Republic. He featured in the quarter final defeat to the [[Czech Republic national under-17 football team|Czech Republic]] on 2 May 1999; he played 61 minutes before being replaced by [[Jay Bothroyd]] as England lost 1\u22120 [[Overtime (sports)#Association football|after extra time]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nv.fotbal.cz/en-national-teams/national-team-u-16/statistics/viewstat2.asp?page=/nat/16/1998/match15.asp |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180722011401/http://nv.fotbal.cz/en-national-teams/national-team-u-16/statistics/viewstat2.asp?page=/nat/16/1998/match15.asp |archivedate=22 July 2018 |title=Z\u00e1pis o utk\u00e1n\u00ed \u010d. 86 |work=Fotbal.cz |publisher=Fotbalov\u00e9 asociace \u010cesk\u00e9 republiky |language=Czech |date=2 May 1999 |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref>FA Handbook1999/2000</ref>\n\n===England futsal===\nSzmid was called up to the [[England national futsal team]] for the Four Nations tournament in March 2005.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.futsalplanet.com/news/news-01.asp?id=4460 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121001101729/http://www.futsalplanet.com/news/news-01.asp?id=4460 |archivedate=1 October 2012 |title=4 Nations tournament |work=FutsalPlanet.com |publisher=Fut5al Planet |date=3 March 2005 |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/Futsal/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2005/03/EngFutsal_Squad_vFrance.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050404024008/http://www.thefa.com:80/England/Futsal/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2005/03/EngFutsal_Squad_vFrance.htm |archivedate=4 April 2005 |title=Dell names new-look squad |work=TheFA.com |publisher=The Football Association |date=1 March 2005 |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> On 9 March, he made his debut against [[France national futsal team|France]] and scored a penalty in the 5\u22122 defeat in [[Villeneuve-d'Ascq]], France.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/Futsal/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2005/03/EngFutsal_France5England2.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050312052045/http://www.thefa.com:80/England/Futsal/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2005/03/EngFutsal_France5England2.htm |archivedate=12 March 2005 |title=French fire in five |work=TheFA.com |publisher=The Football Association |date=9 March 2005 |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> Two days later, he played in the loss against [[Finland national futsal team|Finland]] as England finished last place in the tournament.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/Futsal/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2005/03/EngFutsal_vFinland_Mar05.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050404025217/http://www.thefa.com/England/Futsal/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2005/03/EngFutsal_vFinland_Mar05.htm |archivedate=4 April 2005 |title=Frustration against Finland |work=TheFA.com |publisher=The Football Association |date=11 March 2005 |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{soccerbase|29294}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20020615003942/http://www.southendunited.co.uk/stats/view/player_profiles/0,,10444~22117,00.html Marek Szmid] at SouthendUnited.co.uk\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Szmid, Marek}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Manchester United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Southend United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Sutton Coldfield Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Marine F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Nuneaton Griff F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Nuneaton Borough F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Liverpool John Moores University]]\n[[Category:Vauxhall Motors F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Marek Szmid\n| image          =\n| caption        =\n| fullname       = Marek Andrezj Szmid<ref name=\"hugman\">{{Hugman|19166|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1982|3|2|df=y}}<ref name=\"hugman\"/>\n| birth_place    = [[Nuneaton]], England<ref name=\"hugman\"/>\n| height         = {{height|ft=5|in=8}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southendunited.co.uk/stats/view/player_profiles/0,,10444~22117,00.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020615003942/http://www.southendunited.co.uk/stats/view/player_profiles/0,,10444~22117,00.html |archivedate=15 June 2002 |title=Marek Szmid |work=SouthendUnited.co.uk |publisher=Southend United Football Club |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n| position       = [[Midfielder]]<ref name=\"hugman\"/>\n| youthyears1    = 1998\u20132001<ref name=\"redstat\">{{cite web|url=http://www.redstat.co.uk/?PlayerNo=301 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.vn/o6enu |archivedate=17 April 2020 |title=Marek Szmid |work=redStat.co.uk |publisher=redStat \u2212 Manchester United Statistics |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n| youthclubs1    = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]\n| years1         = 2001\u20132002\n| clubs1         = [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]]\n| caps1          = 2\n| goals1         = 0\n| years2         = 2002\u20132003\n| clubs2         = [[Sutton Coldfield Town F.C.|Sutton Coldfield Town]]\n| caps2          =\n| goals2         =\n| years3         = 2003\n| clubs3         = [[Marine F.C.|Marine]]\n| caps3          =\n| goals3         =\n| years4         = 2003\u20132004\n| clubs4         = [[Nuneaton Griff F.C.|Nuneaton Griff]]\n| caps4          =\n| goals4         =\n| years5         = 2004\u20132005\n| clubs5         = [[Nuneaton Town F.C.|Nuneaton Borough]]\n| caps5          =\n| goals5         =\n| years6         = 2004\u20132005\n| clubs6         = [[Liverpool John Moores University#Sports|Liverpool John Moores University]]\n| caps6          =\n| goals6         =\n| years7         = 2005\u20132006\n| clubs7         = [[Vauxhall Motors F.C.|Vauxhall Motors]]\n| caps7          =\n| goals7         =\n| totalcaps      =\n| totalgoals     =\n| nationalyears1 = 1997\u20131998\n| nationalteam1  = [[ESFA under-15 football team|ESFA U15]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 15\n| nationalgoals1 =\n| nationalyears2 = 1998\u20131999\n| nationalteam2  = [[England national under-16 football team|England U16]]\n| nationalcaps2  = 8\n| nationalgoals2 =\n| nationalyears3 =\n| nationalteam3  = [[England national under-17 football team|England U17]]\n| nationalcaps3  =\n| nationalgoals3 =\n| nationalyears4 = 2005\n| nationalteam4  = [[England national futsal team|England futsal]]\n| nationalcaps4  = 6\n| nationalgoals4 = 1\n}}\n'''Marek Andrezj Szmid''' (born 2 March 1982) is an English retired professional [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[midfielder]].\n\n==Early life==\nSzmid was born in [[Nuneaton]], Warkwickshire.<ref name=\"hugman\"/>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Club career===\nSzmid began his career with the youth team of [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] which he captained and then went on to make several reserve team appearances, before moving to [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]] in November 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/896023.stm|title=Football Transfers|date=1 August 2002|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southendunited.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10444~160586,00.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120531092310/http://www.southendunited.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10444~160586,00.html |archivedate=31 May 2012 |title=\"IT'S A GOOD CLUB\" - MAREK SZMID |work=SouthendUnited.co.uk |publisher=Southend United Football Club |date=17 November 2004 |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> He made 2 appearances in [[the Football League]] for Southend.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/southend/southend.html|title=SOUTHEND UNITED : 1946/47 \u2013 2009/10|publisher=Post War English & Scottish Football League A \u2013 Z Player's Database}}</ref><ref>{{soccerbase|29294}}</ref> Szmid later played non-league football with [[Sutton Coldfield Town F.C.|Sutton Coldfield Town]] and [[Marine F.C.|Marine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nonleaguedaily.com/news/index.php?newsmode=FULL&nid=14132 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121004022117/http://www.nonleaguedaily.com/news/index.php?newsmode=FULL&nid=14132 |archivedate=4 October 2012 |title=Latest Transfers |work=NonLeagueDaily.com |publisher=Baltic Publications Limited |date=29 November 2003 |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\nIn the same season he moved to play for [[Nuneaton Griff F.C.]].<ref>Coventry Evening Telegraph 10/09/2003</ref> In 2004, he played for [[Nuneaton Town F.C.]].<ref>Coventry Evening Telegraph 04/08/2004</ref> The next season saw him playing for [[Vauxhall Motors F.C.|Vauxhall Motors]].<ref>Liverpool Echo 06/08/2005</ref> That season saw him suffering a bad injury which caused him to retire from playing football. After retiring, he attended [[Liverpool John Moores University]] where he graduated with a B.A. in Sports Development in 2007.<ref>Liverpool John Moores University 2007 Graduates Award Ceremony</ref> Whilst studying he suffered a severe injury which caused his playing career to stop. The following year he attended the University of Chester where he took part in the GTP (Graduate Teacher Programme).<ref>University of Chester Graduates Award Ceremony 2008</ref> He started teaching Physical Education at Ashton-on-Mersey School in Trafford in 2008.<ref>http://issuu.com/ashton-on-mersey_school/docs/ashton_magazine_2011</ref> In September 2010 he started work as the Assistant Head of Education and Welfare at Manchester United F.C.<ref>http://youblisher.com/p/238592-Man-U-Tour-Diary-2011/</ref>\n\n===International career===\n===ESFA U15===\nSzmid represented [[ESFA Under-15|ESFA U-15]] and the team reached 3rd place of the mini World Cup at the Montaigu Tournament in France.<ref>ESFA Handbook 1998/99</ref> He was in the last ESFA Under-15 team, when they beat Germany 1\u20130 at the Olympic Stadium Berlin, before the Football Association took over the running of Schools Football. \n\n===England U16===\nSzmid represented [[England national under-16 football team|England]] at [[1999 UEFA European Under-16 Championship]] in the Czech Republic. He featured in the quarter final defeat to the [[Czech Republic national under-17 football team|Czech Republic]] on 2 May 1999; he played 61 minutes before being replaced by [[Jay Bothroyd]] as England lost 1\u22120 [[Overtime (sports)#Association football|after extra time]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nv.fotbal.cz/en-national-teams/national-team-u-16/statistics/viewstat2.asp?page=/nat/16/1998/match15.asp |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180722011401/http://nv.fotbal.cz/en-national-teams/national-team-u-16/statistics/viewstat2.asp?page=/nat/16/1998/match15.asp |archivedate=22 July 2018 |title=Z\u00e1pis o utk\u00e1n\u00ed \u010d. 86 |work=Fotbal.cz |publisher=Fotbalov\u00e9 asociace \u010cesk\u00e9 republiky |language=Czech |date=2 May 1999 |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref>FA Handbook1999/2000</ref>\n\n===England futsal===\nSzmid was called up to the [[England national futsal team]] for the Four Nations tournament in March 2005.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.futsalplanet.com/news/news-01.asp?id=4460 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121001101729/http://www.futsalplanet.com/news/news-01.asp?id=4460 |archivedate=1 October 2012 |title=4 Nations tournament |work=FutsalPlanet.com |publisher=Fut5al Planet |date=3 March 2005 |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/Futsal/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2005/03/EngFutsal_Squad_vFrance.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050404024008/http://www.thefa.com:80/England/Futsal/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2005/03/EngFutsal_Squad_vFrance.htm |archivedate=4 April 2005 |title=Dell names new-look squad |work=TheFA.com |publisher=The Football Association |date=1 March 2005 |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> On 9 March, he made his debut against [[France national futsal team|France]] and scored a penalty in the 5\u22122 defeat in [[Villeneuve-d'Ascq]], France.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/Futsal/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2005/03/EngFutsal_France5England2.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050312052045/http://www.thefa.com:80/England/Futsal/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2005/03/EngFutsal_France5England2.htm |archivedate=12 March 2005 |title=French fire in five |work=TheFA.com |publisher=The Football Association |date=9 March 2005 |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> Two days later, he played in the loss against [[Finland national futsal team|Finland]] as England finished last place in the tournament.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/Futsal/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2005/03/EngFutsal_vFinland_Mar05.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050404025217/http://www.thefa.com/England/Futsal/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2005/03/EngFutsal_vFinland_Mar05.htm |archivedate=4 April 2005 |title=Frustration against Finland |work=TheFA.com |publisher=The Football Association |date=11 March 2005 |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References=